taxonomicNotes: P. arundinacea includes a variety of taxa, including ssp. rotgesii which is endemic to Corsica, some authors treat this taxon as a species in which case it would probably be considered to be of conservation concern.

There are no significant taxonomic issues associated with this name. A. aequalis has been shown to hybridise with A. geniculatus (A. ×haussknechtianus Asch. & Graebn.) which occurs fairly frequently in areas of sympatry but is not considered likely to affect the survival of the species or this evaluation.

A portion of the genus Polygonum was separated as Persicaria leaving only members of the Polygonum aviculare group in the original genus. Whilst generally widely accepted, IPNI (for example) appears to retain Polygonum as the correct genus for this species, under which name it would be P. lapathifolium L. TROPICOS cites Polygonum lapathifolium var. lapathifolium as the accepted name. P. lapathifolium is a very variable taxon, to the extent that Tela Botanica lists 43 sub-specific taxa, but IPNI and TROPICOS list only between 10 and 20. Hybrids have been reported between this taxon and other Persicaria species, but reliable evidence is sparse; as suggested by Flora Nordica hybridisation is likely to be rare and is unlikely to affect the red list assessment. In the Arabian Peninsula, it appears likely that the treatment of taxa such as P. lapathifolia and P. persicaria is not consistent throughout the region.

It is commonly known as Stoneworts. It is submerged aquatic alga with slender plant body which gets differentiated into nodes and internodes. The internodes are corticated. The nodes are provided with stipulode, branches of limited growth and sex organs. The sex organs are male called globule and females as nucule. The nucule lies above the globule.

This species was first described from Sri Lanka, therefore, the name "ceylonica" latinized to "zeylanica" though it was first collected from Central america.

Chara zeylanica is one of the polymorphic species of algae. Examination of 140 collections of Chara zeylanica from 3 southwestern states shows that a strong dichotomy exists in the collections. Some produce 4-plated antheridia while others produce 8-plated antheridia. Absolute separation of the study material is possible on the basis of plate number. In addition, 3 other characters (length/width ratio of oospores; fertility of first branchlet node; and number of distal ecorticate branchlet internodes) show strong correlation with the antheridial type. Preliminary chromosomal work indicates that a segregation at this level may also be possible. In 4-plated collections examined, n = 28; 8-plated collections are usually n = 56; however, a few 8-plated collections are n = 42. No conclusion has been reached regarding the status of the latter collections. Further investigation is needed.
Robust perennial growing usually in tufts, short lignified rhizome abou 1 cm thick, covered with fibres.

Vigna luteola (Jacq.) Benth. is a genepool tertiary wild relative of both Bambara Groundnut [Vigna subterranea (L.) Verdc. var. subterranea (L.) Verdc.] and Cowpea [Vigna unguiculata (L.) Walp. var. unguiculata (L.) Walp.]. The species is also classified in Taxon Group 2 of Bambara Groundnut and Taxon Group 3 of Cowpea (Vincent et al. 2013), following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006).

Vigna marina Merr. comprises two subspecies: subsp. marina and subsp. oblonga (Benth.) Padulosi (Maxted et al. 2004). Vigna marina is also cultivated (USDA, Agricultural Research Service, National Plant Germplasm System 2019) but only wild populations will be considered in this threat assessment. In its wild form, V. marina is a primary wild relative of dine bean, the cultivated form of the species. Vigna marina is a genepool tertiary wild relative of both Bambara Groundnut [Vigna subterranea (L.) Verdc. var. subterranea (L.) Verdc.] and Cowpea [Vigna unguiculata (L.) Walp. var. unguiculata (L.) Walp.]. The species is also classified in Taxon Group 2 of Bambara Groundnut and Taxon Group 3 of Cowpea (Vincent et al. 2013), following the definition of Maxted et al. (2006).

Some authorities treat Schoenoplectus tabernaemontani as a subspecies of S. lacustris (e.g., Sell and Murrell 1996, Castroviejo et al. 2008) while others (such as TROPICOS) maintain it within Scirpus. In Euro-Med checklist this is a synony of S. lacustris subsp. glaucus (Sm.) Bech (Euro+Med PlantBase). 

Schoenoplectus tabernaemontani hybridises with S. triqueter (L.) Palla and is reported to hybridise with S. lacustris, however the latter is unproven whilst the former is not sufficiently frequent to affect the Red List assessment for this species (Jermy et al. 2007).

In Tasmania this taxon is considered to be a hybrid between two other species. The evidence is inconclusive and if of hybrid origin, it is more likely to be a nothospecies than that each individual tree is an F1 only. In cultivation these trees breed true to type.

Callitris macleayana is the only Callitris species restricted to rainforests. It also differs from other Callitris species in some morphological characters of its leaves and cones to the extent that it has previously classified as a monotypic genus (Octoclinis). Recent phylogenies identify this species as sister to all other species in the genus (Piggin and Bruhl 2010).

J. articulatus is known to hybridise with J. acutiflorus (J. ×surrejanus Druce ex Stace & Lambinon), it is not clear to what extent the hybrid may have replaced J. articulatus throughout much of the United Kingdom.
It is commonly known as Bhada in India. Also known as Flat Sedges, Nut Sedges or Umbrella Sedge.
Isoetes coromandelina L. has two subspecies: coromandelina L. and macrotubercolata C.R.Marsden.

According to Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew WCSPF (World Checklist of Selected Plant Families), this genus belongs to the Araceae Family.

This species may be easily confused with Spirodela polyrhiza.
This a member of the Halophila ovalis complex, which is under taxonomic review. Historically, other species currently considered to be in this complex may have been labelled as H. ovalis.
This plant has been considered as a synonym of Blyxa aubertii in the past but they are both now considered as individual species.
This species is part of the P. ostenfeldii complex and is therefore treated as a separate species (Kuo and Cambridge 1984). This species is currently undergoing taxonomic review.

The taxonomy of the Ruppia genus is uncertain due to difficulties of identification. The taxonomy of the Ruppia genus is confused. These species can be extremely morphologically variable and respond differently to differing environmental conditions. Therefore, species identifications often link to differences in environmental conditions.
This species is part of the P. ostenfeldii complex (Kuo and Cambridge 1984). This species is currently undergoing taxonomic review.
Plants with glabrous capsules are sometimes recognised as a distinct species called Dentella serpyllifolia (Cook 1996).
Treated as Najas pseudograminea in the Flora of China (eFlora 2011). Four subspecies have been described (de Wilde 1962).
Two varieties are recognised: the typical variety on mainland Australia and var. papuana in Papua New Guinea and Indonesia.

The genus Wollemia and its only known species W. nobilis were described in 1995 after a grove of unusual conifers was discovered in a remote canyon of Wollemi National Park, southeastern Australia, in 1994 (Jones et al., 1995). The pollen of W. nobilis closely resembles that of Dilwynites, a fossil pollen taxon with a late Tertiary to late Cretaceous distribution (c. 2-91 million years ago; Macphail et al., 1995; Chambers et al., 1998; Dettmann and Jarzen, 2000), including records from Australia, New Zealand, Antarctica and Patagonia (Macphail et al., 2013). The stratigraphic distribution of Dilwynites has been used to construct a fossil record for Wollemia, although at least some Dilwynites records are attributable to Agathis, the sister group to Wollemia (Macphail and Carpenter, 2014). Hence, the genus Wollemia appears to have an extensive fossil record and to have once been much more widely distributed in the Southern Hemisphere. However, there is no definitive evidence to indicate when the extant species W. nobilis evolved
Was previously treated under the genus Sphagnum.

This species has three subspecies. C. maconochiei ssp. maconochiei, C. maconochiei ssp. lanata and C. maconochiei ssp. viridis which are all assessed separately. However, C. maconochiei ssp. lanata is now considered a synonym of
C. maconochiei (Dixon, D., 2004)
This species has three subspecies: Cycas media subsp. media, C. media subsp. banksii and C. media subsp. ensata.

The genus Vanvoorstia contains three species. Vanvoorstia spectabilis and V. coccinea are common tropical (Indo-Pacific, including GBR) species, with the former also recorded from Lord Howe Island. While some confusion exists as to the exact differences between these two species (Price and Scott 1992), both are easily distinguished and considered very different from V. bennettiana, a very much smaller- and finer-meshed species in which the tetrasporangial stichidia are also easily defined.

There are now four species. Eric Coppejans (pers. comm.) indicates that there is a new species he described from East Africa which is probably Critically Endangered: Vanvoorstia incipiens De Clerck, Wynne & Coppejans (Phycologia 38 (1999): 394-400). This newly described species occurs massively in a single (rather small) bay along the east coast of Zanzibar, at about low tide level (large amounts drifting or entangled to other seaweeds in intertidal pools). Coppejans carried out over 200 collecting excursions along the Kenyan, Tanzanian (incl. Zanzibar) coast and NEVER found a single specimen anywhere else than the type locality, where we find it again year after year. It doesn't occur in the neighbouring bays, which look "identical" to this one! If that bay would be disturbed (harbour, oil pollution, etc.) the only known (type) locality would disappear and we would have a similar story there within the same genus!! Apparently some representatives do not succeed in colonizing larger areas!

Lythrum hyssopifolium is one of a complex of small Lythrum species typically occurring in ephemeral wetlands and in association with larger, more permanent wetlands some of which are recognised by some authors as species (e.g. L. thymifolia). Taxonomic treatment of these entities is inconsistent.

Paracoffea brassii J.-F.Leroy (Leroy, 1968) was added to Psilanthus (subgenus Afrocoffea) by Davis (2003) and then due to the placement of Psilanthus into the synonymy of Coffea (Davis et al. 2011) the nomenclatural change to Coffea brassii (J.-F.Leroy) A.P.Davis  was necessary (Davis 2010).

Several national botanical and taxonomic references (e.g., Tela Botanica (2015), the Inventaire National du Patrimoine Naturel  (INPN 2016) and Schede di botanica (Altervista 2016) include Corynephorus divaricatus (Pourr.) Breistr. as synonym of the taxon Corynephorus fasciculatus Boiss. & Reut. 

However (WCSP 2016) consider both taxa to be valid, with C. divaricatus having a primarily eastern Mediterranean distribution, and C. fasciculatus having a primarily western Mediterranean distribution, although the two species partially overlap. Conversely, Euro+Med PlantBase (Valdés and Scholz 2009) considers C. fasciculatus to be a synonym of C. divaricatus.

Brassica elongata Ehrh. comprises five subspecies: B. elongata Ehrh. subsp. elongata, B. elongata subsp. imdrhasiana Quézel, B. elongata subsp. integrifolia (Boiss.) Breistr., B. elongata subsp. pinnatifida (Schmalh.) Greuter & Burdet, and B. elongata subsp. subscaposa (Maire & Weiller) Maire (USDA, Agricultural Research Service, National Plant Germplasm System 2019).Brassica elongata is a gene pool secondary wild relative of broccoli (B. oleracea L. var. italica Plenck), Brussels sprout [B. oleracea L. var. gemmifera (DC.) Zenker], cabbage (B. oleracea var. capitata L.), cauliflower (B. oleracea var. botrytis L.), kale (B. oleracea var. viridis L.) and turnip (B. rapa L.). It is also a gene pool tertiary wild relative of swede (B. napus L. var. napobrassica (L.) Rchb.), oilseed rape (B. napus L. var. napus) and perennial wall rocket [Diplotaxis tenuifolia (L.) DC.] (Vincent et al. 2013).

Maire, B. fruticulosa subsp. fruticulosa, B. fruticulosa subsp. glaberrima (Pomel) Batt., B. fruticulosa subsp. mauritanica (Coss.) Maire, B. fruticulosa subsp. numidica (Coss.) Maire, B. fruticulosa subsp. pomeliana Maire and B. fruticulosa subsp. radicata (Desf.) Batt. (USDA, Agricultural Research Service, National Plant Germplasm System 2019).Brassica fruticulosa is a gene pool tertiary wild relative of Ethiopian cabbage (B. carinata A.Braun), swede (B. napus L. var. napobrassica (L.) Rchb.), oilseed rape (B. napus L. var. napus), black mustard (B. nigra (L.) W. D. J. Koch), turnip (B. rapa L.) and radish (Raphanus sativus L.) (Vincent et al. 2013). It is also a wild relative of broccoli (B. oleracea L. var. italica Plenck), Brussels sprout (B. oleracea L. var. gemmifera (DC.) Zenker), cabbage (B. oleracea var. capitata L.), cauliflower (B. oleracea var. botrytis L.) and kale (B. oleracea var. viridis L.) (Vincent et al. 2013).

Ten varieties are recognized by Pedley in the Flora of Australia Vol. 11B (Orchard and Wilson 2001). It consists of a large complex of variable intergrading and hybridizing forms, some included in these ten varieties, others regarded as separate species: A. ayersiana, A. brachystachya, A. craspedocarpa, A. minyura, A. paraneura and A. ramulosa. These are distinguished mainly by leaf and pod characteristics (Moore 2005).

It resembles the more westerly distributed Acacia oxyclada. According to Maslin this species is probably better treated as an infraspecific taxon of A. oxyclada, but seeds should be examined before any change is made (Orchard and Wilson 2001).

Two varieties are recognized: var. eremophila and var. variabilis. It is related to A. densiflora Morrison. There is further variant, "numerous-nerved variant" not included in this assessment and was treated as A. rigidens Cunn. ex Don by Maslin in Flora of Central Australia (1981) (Orchard and Wilson 2001).
Two subspecies are recognized: subsp. angusta and subsp. excelsa.
Similar to A. erinacea Benth. and A. semicircinalis Maiden & Blakely.

In the past the species has commonly been confused with Acacia microbotrya; their ranges overlap in the Burakin–Trayning area in Western Australia. A. jennerae is normally distinguished by its straighter phyllodes with more numerous glands and its funicle (Orchard and Wilson 2001).
Closely related to Acacia ephedroides Benth.

The Stannary Hills locality given on the T.L.Bancroft paratype is evidently an error for Eidsvold. Pedley reported the species from the Blackdown Tableland but these plants appear not to be A. semirigida. Further information is needed in order to ascertain the status of this entity (Orchard and Wilson 2001).

This species has been erroneously reported as occurring in the Northern Territory. We based the listing on the distribution of the species according to the Flora of Australia as endemic to the Isdell and Drysdale River areas in the Kimberley region (2001). Bentham, treated Acacia platycarpa as a synonym of A. sericata. The two taxa are closely related and would perhaps be best treated as subspecies of a single species, but A. sericata is readily recognized by its densely minutely stellate-velvety phyllodes.
Two known varieties: var. subglauca and var. filiformis Blakely & McKie
Very similar to A. lucyi, with which it is sometimes confused; A. lucyi can be distinguished by the cauliflorous and ramiflorous habit.

This species was known for over 120 years only from the type, a fruiting specimen, the application of the name Bossiaea. oxyclada had been uncertain until recently when specimens collected in the Fitzgerald River National Park enabled the identity of this species to be established (Ross 2006).
Two varieties are recognized var. scarabaeoides and var. pedunculatus.

"In arid areas, taxonomic distinctions are blurred by the occurrence of polyploidy, hybridization and apomixis". Randell and Barlow (1998) circumscription of this species is chosen to assess this taxon. Senna ferraria was originally classified as a subspecies of S. glutinosa, but it does not form hybrid swarms with other members of that group (Moore 2005).

Most Australian "cassias" occur in large and variable populations that integrate into hybrid swarms maintained by asexual and sexual reproduction. This makes it difficult to separate them into species. There are two ways of dealing with this: one way reduces the number of variants formerly regarded as separate species into subspecies of two widespread species, one of which is Senna artimisioides. The other way, is to treat the hybrid forms into "form taxa", where separation is based on appearance but taxonomic rank is not defined. For the purposes of assessing this species we have chosen the first approach. In which case S. artimisioides includes the following: S. artimisioides ssp. alicia, nothossp. artimisioides (Silver Acacia), nothossp. coriacea (Desert Acacia), ssp. filifolia (Desert Acacia), ssp. helmsii (Burnt-leaved Acacia), ssp. oligophylla (Limestone Acacia), ssp. petiolaris (Woody Acacia), nothossp. sturtii (Grey Acacia) and ssp. zygophylla (Punty Acacia) (Moore 2005).

Ornamental species easily recognized by its large green bird-like flowers and grey-tomentose thick soft-wooded stems (Moore 2005). Two subspecies are recognized: subsp. cunninghamii and subsp. sturtii.
Two subspecies are recognized:  subsp. eremaea and subsp. strehlowii. It is sometimes confused with C. novae-hollandiae subsp. lasiophylla (Moore 2005).
Crotalaria naikiana Zate is now treated as a synonym of C. montana according to Ansari (2008) and this assessment is made using this revised taxonomy.

Two known subspecies: subsp. koolgibberah and subsp. pseudinvoluta Verdc.
Differs from Dichrostachys cinerea in numerous respects but most conspicuously in the number of pairs of pinnae and the size of the leaflets.
Dillwynia sieberi Steud. and Dillwynia juniperina Lodd. were both confused under D. juniperina.
Closely resembles Dillwynia rupestris Jobson & P.H. Weston and D. acicularis Sieber ex DC., which are both New South Wales endemics.
Erythrina variegata is a tree usually between 6-12 but up to 20 m, with much branched crown and coral flowers.

This is an extremely variable species, in both leaf shape and size. It resembles Gastrolobium aculeatum, G. euryphyllum, G. triangulare, G. trilobum and G. wonganensis. There are several known varieties.
Several subspecies and varieties of this species are recognized.
Two subspecies are recognized: subsp. cuneifolia and subsp. glabra Keighery.

This species is allied to Acacia doratoxylon which does not occur in Queensland and has smaller flowers, often shorter phyllodes, a better developed rudimentary axis bearing the spikes and seeds with a longer, narrow areole without a pale halo (Orchard and Wilson 2001).

The New South Wales plants differ from those in Victoria in having slightly broader phyllodes with a few, obscure, impressed lateral nerves (laterals normally absent in Victoria) (Orchard and Wilson 2001). In New South Wales it may be confused with Acacia verniciflua. In Victoria it may be confused with A. leprosa. Putative hybrids between A. ausfeldii and A. paradoxa have been reported.
Similar in habit to A. papyrocarpa but has narrower thicker leaves and narrower beaded pods.
It could be confused with A. cupularis, A. harveyi and  A. euthyphylla.
It can hybridize with Acacia aspera in Victoria and A. paradoxa in South Australia. It sometimes resembles A. verniciflua, A. ixiophylla, A. wihelmiana and A. sabulosa.
This species hybridizes with A. fimbriata.
It can be confused with a variant Platylobium formosum with alternate leaves, only fertile specimens can separate both species.

An extremely variable species due mostly to the pubescence. It can be confused with Cullen martinii which has a shorter lower calyx-tooth and few dentate leaflets or with C. virens, which has much shorter leaflets.
In the past this species was recognized as distinct species with a smaller distribution.
There are two known varieties var. glabrescens J.M.Black and  var. villifera.
Rhynchosia minima is exceedingly difficult to divide into lower taxa, its range of variation is very great and experimental techniques are needed (Gillett et al. 1971).
Two known varieties:  var. cannabina and var. sericea (Benth.) N.T.Burb.
It has close affinity with S. macranthum, but it can be easily distinguished by the red base to the wing petals, the prominent keel and the narrower, sparsely fringed stylar wing (Butcher 1998).
Two recognized varieties: var. barbatala from Papua New Guinea and Queensland and var. glabra Bosman & De Haas from Papua New Guinea.

This is a complex taxon and in the past it has been confused with Tephrosia purpurea (L.) Pers., a species from Africa, Asia and northern Australia (Maconochie 1985). Further research is needed to determine whether Australian material is referable to T. purpurea. T. brachyodon is a variable species with several varieties. There is also some confusion between T. laxa var. angustata and T. brachyodon var. multiflora (R.Br.) Domin (Wheeler 1992). Further work is required to define taxon limits (I. Cowie pers. comm. 2010).
Further work is required to define species limits and at least one of the Northern Territory records is a misidentification (I. Cowie pers. comm. 2010).
This species may be a form of Tephrosia remotiflora Benth. (I. Cowie pers. comm. 2010).

Trifolium pratense L. belongs to section Trifolium and is a secondary wild relative of the cultivated crop crimson clover (T. incarnatum L.), as well as a primary wild relative of cultivated T. pratense (USDA, ARS, National Genetic Resources Program 2010).

It has eight subspecies that are native to Europe: T. pratense ssp. baeticum (Boiss.) C. Vicioso, T. pratense ssp. expansum (Waldst. & Kit.) Hausskn., T. pratense ssp. kotulae (Pawl.) Soják, T. pratense ssp. maritimum (Zabel) Rothm., T. pratense ssp. nivale (W.D.J. Koch) Arcang., T. pratense L. ssp. pratense, T. pratense ssp. sativum (Schreb.) Schübl. & G.Martens, and T. pratense ssp. semipurpureum (Strobl) Pignatti. There are a further four varieties of T. pratense that are native to Europe: T. pratense var. americanum Harz, T. pratense var. frigidum Gaudin, var. T. pratense maritimum Zabel, and T. pratense var. pratense.

Dioscorea nummularia Lam. is cultivated throughout Polynesia and Micronesia (Cable and Wilson 1984) but only wild populations will be considered in this assessment. It is therefore a primary wild relative of the Pacific yam, the cultivated form of the species. It is also a primary wild relative of water/greater yam, D. alata L. (Vincent et al. 2013).
Dioscorea transversa R. Br. is a primary wild relative of water/greater yam, D. alata L. (Vincent et al. 2013).
O. australiensis Domin is a secondary wild relative of rice (O. sativa L.) and African rice (O. glaberrima Steud.) (USDA, ARS, National Genetic Resources Program 2017).

The genus Utricularia is taxonomically complex, partly due to the desire of botanists to establish methods of identifying non-flowering populations (particularly in the field), with the consequence that the literature is complicated by vast numbers of unreliable records. Many taxa rarely flower and some have apparently never been known to flower in some regions. The majority of the data presented here is derived from Taylor (1989) which is the most reliable source. Additional information has been used where it is felt that it is both useful and reliable.

U. australis has frequently been confused with U. vulgaris and, in much of the literature it is not possible to know for certain which of the two species is intended or whether a mixture of both is involved (Taylor 1989).

The previous taxonomic concept for N. mirabilis included N. rowanae and N. tenax. N. rowanae was reinstated as a separate species in 2005 (Clarke and Kruger 2005), andN. tenax was described as a separate species in 2006 (Clarke and Kruger 2006).

There are two subspecies; A. aemula subsp. aemula is found across the range of the species, whereas A. aemula subsp. muricata is mainly found around the Stirling Range with one record near Esperance (Orchard and Wilson 2001).

The Alpine Wattle is similar to Acacia longifolia but differs by the shape of the phyllodes, its low habit and preference for alpine and subalpine habitats (Orchard and Wilson 2001). There is one specimen at Leiden herbarium named as Acacia alpina, collected by W.Forsyth in 1907 in the Blue Mountains near Sydney. However this species has not been recorded in any floras (for example, Orchard and Wilson 2001) as occurring in the Blue Mountains. Therefore this specimen is excluded from this assessment and further research into the identity of this specimen is recommended.

There is one herbarium specimen at New York botanic gardens collected from South Australia (collector M.H.Nee 45577) which is verified as Acacia c.f. aphylla. This record is over 2,000 km2 from the known range of this species and is therefore excluded from this assessment. However further research into the identity of this specimen is recommended.

Wyrilda was considered in the 1948 Flora of Australia as a synonym of Acacia retinodes but after more herbarium collections were made in 1968 it was recognised again as a separate species (Whibley and Symon 1992).
Acacia euthyphylla is similar to A. crassiuscula but the later species prefers granite habitats and there are differences in the phyllode and flower morphology (Orchard and Wilson 2001).
This Acacia has similar phyllodes and flowers to Acacia racospermoides which is also found on Hinchinbrook Island and the two species have been confused in the past (Orchard and Wilson 2001).

The Gibson Wattle was first collected in 1965 and described in 1999 (DEC 2009). It is sometimes confused with the closely related Acacia kochii which is also found in the same area as this species (Patrick 2001).

There are three accepted varieties; Acacia lanigera var. lanigera, A. lanigera var. gracilipes and A. lanigera var. whanii (Orchard and Wilson 2001). A. lanigera var. venulosa is now recognised as a separate species, A. venulosa (Orchard and Wilson 2001).
A summary of the nomenclatural history of this species is provided by Maslin (Maslin 1994).

There is one herbarium specimen (collected by P.E. Conrick 1165) which was collected in the Northern Territory, far from the range of this Acacia species. It is though to resemble this Acacia species (Orchard and Wilson 2001) but has also been identified as Acacia perryi, a closely related species. This specimen is excluded from this assessment but further research on its identity is recommended.
This species is closely related to Acacia omophylla. In Queensland both species are known as "Yarran" (Orchard and Wilson 2001b).
There are two subspecies, Acacia neurophylla subsp. neurophylla and A.neurophylla subsp. erugata, both are found across the range of the species (Orchard and Wilson 2001).
It was confirmed that Acacia crassifrugis is a synonym of A. pachycarpa after further study of plant material from the Tanami desert region (Maconochie 1978).
This Acacia was first described as Acacia gonophylla var. crassifolia in 1864, but in 1999 it was recognized at species level (Orchard and Wilson 2001).

There are two varieties distinguished by their habit, branch indumentum and their ecological preferences (Orchard and Wilson 2001). Acacia phlebopetala var. phlebopetala is found across the range of the species whilst A. phlebopetala var. pubescens is only found in a small area of Fitzgerald River National Park.
This species was first collected in 1977 and known as Acacia sp. (Wongan Hills) until the species was formally described in 1995 (Maslin 1995, Holland et al. 1997).

This species was original published with the spelling Acacia resinocostata (Pedley 1974). A new combination was published in the genus Racosperma (Pedley 1987) with a different spelling as Racosperma resinicostata. The International Plants Names Index team at the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, following the articles and recommendations in the International Code of Nomenclature for plants (ISPT 2012), recommend using the original spelling for the species epithet "resinocostata".

Specimens from Blackdown Tableland originally named as this Acacia species were later described as a different species, Acacia hendersonii (Orchard and Wilson 2001).

This Acacia along with six other species forms the "Acacia ulicifolia group" which are distinguished by several morphological characters of the phyllodes and flowers (Orchard and Wilson 2001). A full list of synonyms of this Acacia can be found in the Flora of Australia (Orchard and Wilson 2001).
The species was first described in 1990 from the type specimen collected in 1905 (Cowan and Maslin 1990). Since 2003 six further herbarium specimens of this species have been collected.
The Flora of Australia (Wilson 2009) suggests due to several morphological characters that the placement of this species in the genus Glyceria warrants review.

Curcuma australascia Hook. F. (Australian wild turmeric) has been reported to be closely related to the crop species turmeric, C. longa L. (Nicholson and Nicholson 1988). However, a recent phylogeny of the genus Curcuma L. (Záveská et al. 2012) did not include C. australasica   so it is unclear how closely related the two species are. However, both species are within Curcuma subgenus Curcuma (Leong-Škorničková et al. 2015), therefore, until further research is undertaken into the genetic relationships between the species, following the method of Maxted et al. (2006), C. australasica can be classified as a tertiary wild relative (in Taxon Group 3) of turmeric. In its wild form, C. australasica is a primary wild relative of the cultivated form of the species used for ornamental purposes.

Great variability, especially in degree of indumentum and leaf shape, has led to recognition of many microspecies and infraspecific taxa that are not satisfactorily separated when the species is investigated over its geographic range. Apparent hybridization between Lythrum salicaria and L. virgatum and among the many races of L. salicaria in eastern Europe and Asia has further confused the taxonomy (Haining Qin and Shirley A. Graham in Flora of China).
There are no significant taxonomic issues associated with this name.

Rorippa sylvestris (L.) Besser is a wild relative of watercress, Nasturtium officinale W.T. Aiton and N. microphyllum Boenn. ex Rchb. Two subspecies are native to Europe: R. sylvestris ssp. kerneri (Menyh.) Soó and R. sylvestris (L.) Besser ssp. sylvestris.

C. pseudocyperus has been shown to hybridise with C. rostrata (C. ×justischmidtii Junge) and C. vesicaria (Jermy et al. 2007). However, neither of these hybrids is frequent and they are not considered likely to affect the survival of the species or this evaluation.

Agrostis stolonifera L. is a wild relative of the cultivated form, creeping bent grass.

Valdés and Scholz; with contributions from Raab-Straube and Parolly (2009) recognize seven subspecies which are native to Europe: A. stolonifera ssp. albida (Trin.) Tzvelev, A. stolonifera ssp. filfiolia (Link) H. Scholz, A. stolonifera ssp. gaditana (Boiss. & Reut.) Valdés & H. Scholz, A. stolonifera ssp. maritima (Lam.) Vasc., A. stolonifera ssp. scabriglumis (Boiss. & Reut.) Maire, A. stolonifera ssp. stolonifera and A. stolonifera ssp. straminea (Hartm.) Tzvelev. However, the subordinate taxa are poorly defined and taxonomic recognition between authors is inconsistent. It is therefore unlikely that taxonomic issues will affect the conservation or Red List assessment of this species.

G. fluitans has been shown to hybridise with G. notata (G. ×pedicellata F. Towns.) and G. declinata. However, neither of these hybrids is frequent and they are not considered likely to affect the survival of the species or this evaluation.

G. notata has been shown to hybridise with G. fluitans (G. ×pedicellata F. Towns.), however, although this hybrid is locally frequent and it is not considered likely to affect the survival of the species or this evaluation.
Two taxa are sometimes recognised within J. bulbosus: J. bulbosus L. and J. kochii F.W. Schultz. The validity of J. kochii is still uncertain.
M. spicata is known to hybridise with a number of other Mentha species.

This species has several synonyms, some have recently been separated from Caladenia dimorpha and Jones (2007) provides an account of the separation of these species when describing Stegostyla ustulata. However, the scientific evidence is still debated. Examination of the material from across the range and DNA analysis suggests that the delimitation of the species may be inconsistent and observed differences may have an ecological rather than a genetic basis in some cases (M.Clements pers. comm. 2014).
Sorghum interjectum Lazarides is a tertiary wild relative of sorghum, Sorghum bicolor (L.) Moench ssp. bicolor (USDA, ARS, National Resources Program 2015).
Sorghum angustum S. T. Blake is a tertiary wild relative of sorghum, Sorghum bicolor (L.) Moench (Vincent et al. 2013)
Sorghum stipoideum (Ewart & Jean White) C. A. Gardner & C. E. Hubb. is a tertiary wild relative of sorghum, Sorghum bicolor (L.) Moench ssp. bicolor (Vincent et al. 2013).

Recent phylogenetic research (Clements et al. 2011) lends support to the approach followed by some authors of treating this species under the genus Oligochaetochilus, however, further research is required to clarify the relationships.

The correct etymology for this species is actually Nepenthes rowaniae, rather than Nepenthes rowanae. However, when the species was published, the latter spelling was used. In publications, both names are used and are understood by scientists.

N. rowanae was previously included as a synonym of N. mirabilis, until Clarke and Kruger (2005) reinstated it as a separate species.
Nepenthes tenax was previously included within N. mirabilis, until Clarke and Kruger (2006) described it as a separate species.

Rubus ellipticus Sm. is a primary genetic relative of the red raspberry, R. idaeus L. (USDA, Agricultural Research Service, National Plant Germplasm System 2019). The synonymy of R. ellipticus Sm. requires clarification as there is a lack of consensus among published sources as to its synonymy (Evans et al. 2007). For example, Plants of the World Online lists just two synonyms, while the Medicinal Plant Names Services, using unpublished World Checklist data, includes 13 scientific synonyms. The synonyms listed are those cited by at least one of the following taxonomic sources: Plants of the World Online; Medicinal Plant Names Service or GRIN taxonomy (Board of Trustees, RBG Kew 2019a, Board of Trustees, RBG Kew 2019b, USDA, Agricultural Research Service, National Plant Germplasm System 2019). Of these, the most commonly applied are R. ellipticus Sm. var. ellipticus and R. ellipticus Sm. var. obcordatus (Franche.) Focke (CABI 2019).
Echinochloa polystachya  (Kunth) Hitche is a gene pool tertiary wild relative of White millet/ Siberian millet (Echinochloa frumenlacca Link) (Vincent et al. 2013)

Quince, Cydonia oblonga Mill., is cultivated globally as a crop for fruit production (Kafkas et al. 2018). Accordingly, wild quince is a wild relative of cultivated quince under Taxon Group 1b, according to the taxon group definition by Maxted et al. (2006).

In an area of southern Queensland around Inglewood Eucalyptus moluccana intergrades with E. woollsiana. However, typically the leaves of E. moluccana are broader than 3 cm and E. woollsiana substantially narrower and this character can be used to separate the species throughout most of their range.

Eucalyptus ancophila is considered synonymous with E. paniculata (Nicolle 2018). This species is also considered to be taxonomically uncertain by G. Phillips (pers. comm. 2019) and A. Bean (pers. comm. 2019). Eucalyptus ancophila species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) hence both species are assessed separately until the taxonomy is resolved.
There are two recognised varieties of this species Celtis philippensis var. wightii and var. philippensis.
This species is often confused with Fimbristylis miliacea in Indian floristic works. Fimbristylis miliacea is mostly common in north India (Cook 1996).

M. fontana has been taxonomically divided into a series of varieties, subspecies or even species. Recognition of these entities is very inconsistent and there appears to be no useful solution to sub-specific treatment of this taxon.

The genus Utricularia is taxonomically complex, partly due to the desire of botanists to establish methods of identifying non-flowering populations (particularly in the field), with the consequence that the literature is complicated by vast numbers of unreliable records. Many taxa rarely flower and some have apparently never been known to flower in some regions. The majority of the data presented here is derived from Taylor (1989) which is the most reliable source. Additional information has been used where it is felt that it is both useful and reliable.
Subpopulations formerly included in Cycas brunnea, from Wollogorang, are now considered to be Cycas angulata.

This species was known to have three subspecies. Cycas arnhemica ssp. arnhemica, C. arnhemica ssp. muninga and C. arnhemica ssp. natja. However, these subspecies are no longer recognised as distinct from one another (Dixon 2004).
Subpopulations formerly included in this species, from Wollogorang, are now considered to be Cycas angulata.

This species was previously divided into two subspecies of which C. canalis ssp. canalis was listed as Endangered and C. canalis ssp. carinata was listed as Least Concern. The current taxonomic treatment considers this to be a single species with no subspecies.
Recently transferred to Racosperma crassicarpum (A. Cunn. ex Benth.) Pedley.

DNA sequencing is providing evidence that some widespread species of Aglaia should be subdivided. So far, we only have sequences from the western part of the range of Aglaia spectabilis. Future work might lead to the eastern populations being recognised as distinct (Pannell pers. comm. 2017).

Carissa spinarum L. has quite a diverse morphology and is used locally across its range for its edible fruit. Leeuwenberg and van Dilst (2001) acknowledged the earlier name of C. spinarum attributed by Carl Linné in his 1771 Mantissa Plantarum and relegated all subsequent names to junior synonymy. This has resulted in the accumulation of at least 70 synonyms across the genera Antura, Arduina, Cabucala, Carissa, Damnacanthus, Carandas and Jasminonerium (Board of Trustees, RBG Kew 2019, WCSP 2019), with some sources citing as many as 94 (Ansari and Patil 2018). The synonyms listed are some that appear most commonly in the literature. Of particular note is the widely used Carissa edulis (Forssk.) Vahl, which was the name assigned to the species in the Floras of West Tropical Africa, Zambesiaca and East Tropical Africa.

Ipomoea littoralis Blume is in the section Batatas (Khoury et al. 2015). It has long been confused with I. gracilis R.Br., a distinct species which is endemic to Australia, but it is now recognised as a separate species (Austin 1991). It is a secondary genetic relative and potentially the progenitor of Sweet Potato, I. batatas (L.) Lam. var. batatas (L.) Lam. (Vincent et al. 2013, USDA, Agricultural Research Service, National Plant Germplasm System 2018).
There are no significant taxonomic issues associated with this name.
This species' eastern Pacific distribution is now known as R. samoensis.
There are no significant taxonomic issues associated with this name.

There is some uncertainty over the taxonomy and distribution of Ceratopteris thalictroides and C. cornuta. Verdcourt (1999) includes the two as a single taxon, with justification. Al Khulaidi (in prep.) lists only C. cornuta from Yemen, while Hassler and Schmidt (2011) list them as separate species, with C. thalictroides absent from the Arabian Peninsula and C. cornuta occurring in Oman and Yemen (including Soqotra), as does The Plant List. For now, the two taxa are assessed separately for the IUCN Red List.

Although there is some uncertainty regarding the taxonomy of populations close to A. plantago-aquatica in Asia, these do not affect evaluation of the species in Europe.

Plants with the leaves similar to that of A. plantago-aquatica, styles as in A. gramineum and 0.2-0.3 mm long undeveloped anthers are known from Orenburg Region (basin of the Ural and Samara Rivers). Apparently this is the result of hybridization of A. plantago-aquatica × A. gramineum and possibly sterile. These are known as A. ×bjorkqvistii Tzvel. (Tzvelev 2001). This hybridisation is not sufficiently frequent to affect evaluation of the species.

A. plantago-aquatica is reported to hybridise occasionally with A. lanceolatum (A. ×rhicnocarpum Schotsm.) but this is not sufficiently frequent to affect evaluation of the species in Europe.

Throughout much of its range, Juncus bufonius represents a complex of taxa. TROPICOS lists 80 sub-specific combinations for this name, but Flora Europaea volume 5 lists the following as falling within the J. bufonius group: J. bufonius L., J. foliosus Desf., J. hybridus Brot., J. minutulus (Albert & Jahand.) Prain, J. ranarius Nees and J. sorrentini Parl. Some of these are recognized in some countries or by some authors but use is not consistent, thus, for example in the UK J. minutulus is considered a synonym of J. bufonius, while J. ranarius is treated as s synonym of J. ambiguus Guss., equally TROPICOS treats J. hybridus as a nomenclatural synonym of J. bufonius L. but IPNI does not. Work is needed to achieve a degree of consistency in recording of taxa within the J. bufonius group. Kirschner (2002) treats Juncus hybridus (= ambiguus), and J. ranarius as distinct species and does not include them in J. bufonius.
There are no significant taxonomic issues associated with this name.
The name is currently applied to a complex of one widespread species and a few stenoendemic species (J. Leong-Škornicková pers. comm.).

Stictocardia tiliifolia has been confused with Ipomoea campanulata L. ( = S. campanulata (L.) Merr.), which is similar in general appearance and grows also along seacoasts. The glandular-dotted leaves, calyx, and corolla, and the non-capsular fruits enclosed in enlarged, leathery sepals are distinctive for S. tiliifolia. The nomenclature for S. tiliifolia has been the subject of some disagreement, and of the two different interpretations proposed, Austin et al. (Brittonia 30: 195-198. 1978) and Gunn (Brittonia 24: 169-176. 1972), the former is followed here.
Solanum viarum Dunal is a tertiary wild relative of aubergine/egg plant, S. melongena L. (Vincent et al. 2013).

Sorghum plumosum (R.Br.) P.Beauv. is a tertiary wild relative of sorghum, S. bicolor (L.) Moench, and Sudan grass, S. x drummondii (Nees ex Steud.) Millsp. & Chase (USDA, Agricultural Research Service, National Plant Germplasm System 2019).
Plants which are intermediate between A. barbigerus and A. obovatus in terms of their leaf shape may be of hybrid origin.
Adenanthos cuneatus apparently hybridises readily with others, and putative hybrids between it and A. dobsonii, A. apiculatus and A. sericeus (A. × cunninghamii) have been reported.

There are two subspecies. Adenanthos cygnorums subsp. cygnorum occurs from Kojonup north to the Murchison River and from Perth east to Wickepin. Adenanthos cygnorum subsp. chamaephyton is confined to a few areas near Mundaring and Chidlow, in the Darling Range east of Perth.

The differences between the two subspecies are relatively minor; the most significant being habit. As prostrate plants are found in other species (e.g. A. pungens ), the distinction does not warrant recognition at a higher status. Adenanthos cygnorum was formerly included in A. sericeus, but the two species are easily distinguished by flower colour.
A hybrid with A. obovatus is frequent (A. × pamela).

There is currently question over whether A. eyrei is a distinct species due to its similarity to A. forrestii. Key differences between the two species appears to be the absence of a lignotuber in A. eyrei as opposed to its presence in A. forrestii, and the colour of the flowers, with A. eyrei having dark crimson flowers and A. forrestii having pale red and cream flowers.

However, recent observation has shown the flower colour of both taxa to be variable and the lack of a lignotuber and the lack of a woody underground rootstock are not normally used to distinguish taxa at a species level without additional morphological features (Brown et al. 1998). A taxonomic review of A. eyrei is currently being carried out and a DNA analysis may follow (DEC 2009).
A hybrid with A. cuneatus has been found on two occasions.

This species is not closely related to others, except perhaps A. argyreus. The flowers are similar, but A. gracilipes has remarkable sclerified leaves. The only other species with terete, rigid leaves is A. pungens; its leaves, however, are sharply pointed.
There are two recognised subspecies; macrantha and ericifolia
There are two varieties: between Tathra National Park and Moora occurs var. leptophylla, while B. leptophylla var. melletica occurs near the lower west coast between Kalbarri and Guilderton.

There are two varieties that occur as follows: var. nutans from the east side of the Pallinup River to Israelite Bay; and var. cernuella from the Stirling Range to Albany, and east almost to the Pallinup River, with outlying populations near Woodanilling.

Banksia recurvistylis K.R.Thiele is described to accommodate anomalous populations previously referred to B. meganotia (A.S.George) A.R.Mast & K.R.Thiele. The new species differs from B. meganotia in its habit and flower and leaf dimensions, and is geographically disjunct. Both B. meganotia and B. recurvistylis have relatively restricted distributions and are of conservation significance (Thiele 2009).

Two subspecies are recognised: Conospermum acerosum Lindl. subsp. acerosum occurs from south of Northampton to near Perth, with a few, isolated populations near Busselton and Nannup; and Conospermum acerosum subsp. hirsutum occurs from Northampton north to Kalbarri.

Two subspecies are recognised: Conospermum amoenum Meisn. subsp. amoenum is common in the Darling Scarp, extending from Waroona to Dalwallinu; and Conospermum amoenum subsp. cuneatum occurs between Dryandra and York. This subspecies is not as common as subsp. amoenum.

There are six subspecies: Conospermum caeruleum R.Br. subsp. caeruleum is common from Denmark to east of Albany; C. caeruleum subsp. oblanceolatum occurs between Mt Barker and the Stirling Range; C. caeruleum subsp. contortum only known from the type collection; C. caeruleum subsp. debile occurs in swampy areas from Busselton to Scott River; C. caeruleum subsp. spathulatum occurs from Donnybrook south to Albany; and C. caeruleum subsp. marginatum occurs from the vicinity of Busselton to Scott River.

Three subspecies are recognised: Conospermum capitatum subsp. velutinum common in the Albany area, north to Mt Barker and in the Porongurup Range; C. capitatum Meisn. subsp. capitatum occurs in the south-western coastal regions of Western Australia; C. capitatum subsp. glabratum is widespread between Perth and Nannup.

There are two subspecies: Conospermum flexuosum Meisn. subsp. flexuosum, that occurs in the Albany area, south of the Stirling Range and east to Wellstead; and C. flexuosum subsp. laevigatum, which occurs in the Capel–Busselton area and east to Nannup, with an isolated collection from Waroona.

There are two subspecies. Conospermum leianthum (Benth.) Diels subsp. leianthum occurs between Forrestania and east of Esperance. Conospermum leianthum subsp. orientale E.M.Benn. occurs from c. 10 km east of Esperance to Israelite Bay.

Three subspecies are recognised:

Conospermum longifolium subsp. longifolium
Conospermum longifolium subsp. mediale
Conospermum longifolium subsp. angustifolium

Two subspecies are recognised: Conospermum stoechadis Endl. subsp. stoechadis, which is widespread throughout south-western Western Australia, from Kalbarri east to Bungalbin Hill and south to Lake Grace; the second subspecies, C. stoechadis subsp. sclerophyllum occurs from Jurien Bay east to Kulin and south to Wickepin.
Two subspecies are recognised; subsp. bipinnatifida occurs from the Darling Plateau east of Perth south to Manjimup while subsp. multifida occurs between Eneabba and Muchea.

There are two varieties: Banksia erythrocephala C.A.Gardner var. erythrocephala with the same distribution as the species; and B. erythrocephala var. inopinata, recorded near Dumbleyung, Kulin and Nyabing, south-western Western Australia.

Phylogenies inferred from both chloroplast and nuclear DNA regions have placed the southwest Australian genus Dryandra R. Br. (93 spp.) among the descendants of the most recent common ancestor of the more widespread Australian genus Banksia L.f. (80 spp.) (Mast and Thiele 2007).
There is an unsubscribed subspecies from close to Toodyay. B. n. Mornagup.
The subspecies occur as follows: subsp. nobilis between Walebing and Katanning and subsp.fragrans between Eneabba and Badgingarra.
There are two varieties: Banksia undata var. undata occurs between Clackline and Dwellingup; Banksia undata var. splendens occurs from the Brookton Hwy south to Bannister.

There are two subspecies: Banksia squarrosa subsp. squarrosa occurs throughout the range of the species except near the Whicher Range and B. squarrosa subsp. argillacea occurs on the coastal plain close to the western base of the Whicher Range, east of Busselton.
There are two varieties, Banksia subpinnatifida var. subpinnatifida occurs between Pingelly and Narrogin; B. subpinnatifida var. imberbis occurs between Boddington and Broomehill.

Grevillea agrifolia A.Cunn. ex R.Br. subsp. agrifolia occurs in Western Australia and Northern Territory, widespread in the south-western and eastern Kimberley, including offshore islands and as far S as Halls Creek, and in the Northern Territory in the north-western part of Victoria River district (e.g. Timber Ck, Jasper Gorge). 

Grevillea agrifoliasubsp. microcarpa occurs in the northern Kimberley region of Western Australia, where confined to the area between Napier Broome Bay and the Drysdale and King Edward Rivers.

There are three subspecies:

Grevillea amplexans F.Muell. ex Benth. subsp. amplexans occurs from east of Geraldton, south to Watheroo and Coomberdale.

Grevillea amplexans subsp. semivestita occurs in south-western Western Australia, in the area from Watheroo National Park to Yarra Yarra Lakes (just west of Carnamah).

Grevillea amplexans subsp. adpressa occurs in south-western Western Australia, between Mingenew and Watheroo.

There are two subspecies.

Grevillea biformis Meisn. subsp. biformis is widespread in south-western Western Australia, in the northern, central and southern wheatbelt regions from Shark Bay and Murchison River to Lake Grace and Hyden.

The second subspecies, Grevillea biformis subsp. cymbiformis is found in a small area S and SSW of Eneabba, Western Australia.

Grevillea coccinea coccinea is widespread south from the Ravensthorpe Range to the coast and west towards Mount Manypeaks, Western Australia. Grevillea coccinea lanata occurs in south-western Western Australia from Thumb Peak to Middle Mount Barren in Fitzgerald River National Park.

There are two subspecies. Grevillea didymobotrya didymobotrya occurs in south-western Western Australia, widespread from the Shark Bay area inland to Cundeelee and south to Balladonia and Ravensthorpe; Grevillea didymobotrya involuta occurs in south-western Western Australia, between Geraldton and Mullewa.
The species is placed as a replacement synonym of Grevillea neodissecta I.M.Turner by FloraBase, following Turner (2014).
This species is currently under revision and two new taxa are expected to be recognised (P. Olde pers. comm. 2018).

Two subspecies are recognised.

Grevillea insignis Kippist ex Meisn. subsp. insignis occurs in the inland south-west of Western Australia between Tammin, Nyabing and Tarin Rock, and a disjunct population to the east of Perth near Quarading.

Grevillea insignis subsp. elliotii occurs in the inland south-west of Western Australia, restricted to an area east of Varley between Hatters Hill and Middle Ironcap (S of Lake Cronin).

There are three subspecies.

Grevillea manglesii subsp. ornithopoda occurs in south-western Western Australia, in the SW part of the species range, in the Darling Range from Jarrahdale and Pinjarra to Mt William E of Cookerup.

Grevillea manglesii (Graham) Planch. subsp. manglesii occurs in south-western Western Australia, in the northern part of the species range, in the Darling Range between Wooroloo and Mundaring Weir–Helena Valley, and S to Mt Dale.

Grevillea manglesii subsp. dissectifolia occurs in south-western Western Australia, in the SE part of the species range, in the Darling Range from Dwellingup and North Bannister N to Gleneagle.

Three subspecies are currently recognised.

Grevillea obliquistigma subsp. cullenii occurs in the inland south-west of Western Australia; known from near Laverton and possibly also Cosmo Newberry (cited in D.J.McGillivray & Makinson, Grevillea 153 (1993), specimen not seen).

Grevillea obliquistigma C.A.Gardner subsp. obliquistigma occurs in south-western Western Australia, where widespread from the lower Murchison River inland to Mount Magnet and S towards Bullfinch.

Grevillea obliquistigma subsp. funicularis occurs in the inland south-west of Western Australia, in the area bounded by Morawa, Mingenew and Ballidu.

There are three forms. The 'type form' ('typical form' of Olde & Marriott, Grevillea Book 3: 69 (top right & 50A), 70 (50B, C) (1995)) is an upright, usually single-stemmed shrub 2–3 m tall, with entire leaves 1–1.2 mm wide; it occurs mainly in the northern part of the range (Boorabbin, Coolgardie, Kalgoorlie), with a disjunct occurrence S of Norseman. Lignotuberous reproduction has not been confirmed for this form.

The 'coarse-leaved form' tends to have mixed entire and 2- or 3-lobed leaves, with leaves and lobes 1.5–2 mm wide; it is lower-growing (0.5–2 m), lignotuberous, and quite often multistemmed; it occurs in the Lake King–Hyden area and Frank Hann National Park.

The 'pinnate-leaved form' occurs between Peak Charles and Salmon Gums; it has most or all leaves 3–7-lobed, the segments c. 1.0–1.2 mm wide, and a compact habit with lignotuberous reproduction.

The 'type form' ('form n' of McGillivray & Makinson, Grevillea 176–180 (1993)) occurs around Burracoppin, Kellerberrin, Yorkrakine, Cunderdin, Quairading, and Beverley, and from Wongan Hills to Ballidu; it has glabrous and glaucous branchlets, glabrous floral rachises, and leaves tripartite or sometimes biternate.

The 'hairy form' (forms 'm' and 'o' of McGillivray & Makinson, loc. cit.), occurs around Goomalling and Manmanning, and between Pingelly, Quairading and Northam; it has subsericeous to tomentose branchlets and (usually) floral rachises. 'Form j' of McGillivray & Makinson (loc. cit. ) occurs between Merredin and Bonnie Rock, and has branchlets and floral rachises glabrous, leaves 3–5-partite with frequent secondary division and rather short lobes.

The 'granite form' ('form l' of McGillivray & Makinson, loc. cit.) occurs around Warralakin, Muntadgin and Mt Caroline; it has branchlets and floral rachises glabrous and glaucous, leaves with 3–5 primary lobes and usually with secondary division, and the unit conflorescences sometimes shortly cylindrical; this form is superficially very similar to G. xiphoideawhich also grows near Muntadgin, but the latter species has smooth fruits, and floral rachises more than 20 mm long (the second feature also distinguishes G. elongata).

A small-fruited form (follicles 6–7 mm long, pedicels c. 5 mm long) is recorded for c. 30 km E of Hyden (P. Gullan pers. comm.).

There are four subspecies; Grevillea pauciflora R.Br. subsp. pauciflora occurs in South Australia, widespread on Eyre and Yorke peninsulas and on Kangaroo Island; subsp. leptophylla occurs in South Australia, only on the Eyre Peninsula, N and NW of Cummins; subsp. psilophylla occurs near the south coast of Western Australia between Aroona Station (east of Esperance) and Point Malcolm; subsp. saxatilis is confined to Mt. Ragged, N of Cape Arid, Western Australia, near the western end of the Great Australian Bight.

Three subspecies are recognised: Grevillea petrophiloides Meisn. subsp. petrophiloides occurs in south-western Western Australia, from the lower Murchison River south to Quairading and about Hyden; Grevillea petrophiloides subsp. magnifica occurs in south-western Western Australia, restricted to the area between Tammin and about Pantapin; Grevillea petrophiloides subsp. remota occurs in inland south-western Western Australia, known only from a few sites from near Varley to Norseman.
This species is under taxonomic revision.

There are three subspecies.

Grevillea pyramidalis subsp. longiloba occurs in Northern Territory, mainly in the Katherine area (E of Scott Creek to Katherine Gorge National Park) on the S end of the Pinkerton Range, and one record from c. 33 km SW of Borroloola.

Grevillea pyramidalis A.Cunn. ex R.Br. subsp. pyramidalis occurs in north-western Western Australia, from about Broome N to the Prince Regent River and often within 50 km of the coast, with an isolated occurrence in the McLarty Hills.

Grevillea pyramidalis subsp. leucadendron occurs in north-western Western Australia (Pilbara and Hamersley Range to Halls Creek and northern and eastern Kimberley), and western Northern Territory (scattered in the Victoria River district and almost to Katherine). Not known to occur at Shark Bay as given on the holotype of G. obliqua.

Two subspecies are recognised.

Grevillea refracta R.Br. subsp. refracta occurs in Western Australia and Northern Territory widespread N of about latitude 21ºS, including coastal islands, and in north-western Queensland between Mt Isa and Camooweal.

Grevillea refracta subsp. glandulifera occurs in Western Australia on the Ord River catchment between the Carr Boyd Range, Spring Creek and Kununurra, and extending just into Northern Territory in the Pinkerton Range area.

There are six subspecies: subsp. sarissa occurs in inland south-western Western Australia, widespread in the area bounded by Jibberding, Mt Magnet, Lake Seabrook, Laverton and Blue Robin Hill (NE of Queen Victoria Spring); subsp. umbellifera occurs in South Australia in the NW of the Eyre Peninsula, between about Koonibba and Karcultaby; subsp. succincta occurs in inland central Western Australia, around Wiluna (extending c. 100 km W and S of the town and up to c. 400 km N and E); subsp. anfractifolia occurs in inland south-western Western Australia, from Norseman to Balladonia and N to Coolgardie and Queen Victoria Spring; subsp. rectitepala occurs in inland southern Western Australia, known from a few collections only, between Comet Vale and Cundeelee; subsp. bicolor occurs in inland central Western Australia, known from the Cue to Lake Austin area and S of Wiluna.

Three subspecies are recognised: Grevillea shuttleworthiana subsp. canarina is found in south-western Western Australia from Binnu (SE of Kalbarri) S to c. Mullering Brook and E to Piawaning.

Grevillea shuttleworthiana subsp. obovata occurs in south-western Western Australia from Mt Jackson and Bronti S to the Ravensthorpe Range, and W to Lake Grace.

Grevillea shuttleworthiana Meisn. subsp. shuttleworthiana is found in south-western Western Australia from Perenjori and Bonnie Rock S to Yorkrakine

Four formal subspecies, and one informal subspecies, are recognised.

Grevillea synapheae R.Br. subsp. synapheae occurs in the south-west of Western Australia, where fairly common in and east of the Darling Range, from Perth suburbs south-east to Narrogin and Williams, north almost to Gingin, and north-east to near Toodyay.

Grevillea synapheae subsp. A occurs in south-western Western Australia, known only from Mt. Misery near Dandaragan.

Grevillea synapheae subsp. latiloba occurs in south-western Western Australia, north of Perth between about Bindoon and Mogumber.

Grevillea synapheae subsp. pachyphylla occurs in the north of the species range, from the Badgingarra area north to Eneabba.

Grevillea synapheae subsp. minyulo occurs in southwest of Western Australia, in the Dandaragan–Cataby area.
This species need a taxonomic review, and a preliminary treatment is forthcoming (P. Olde pers. comm. 2019).
This species is under revision.

There are some inconsistencies between the description in the protologue and features of the taxon long recognised as G. vestita; in addition the species is not known to occur at the type location of King Georges Sound, although that place name was often used loosely. In the absence of the type, past usage is maintained. See protologue and McGillivray & Makinson (Grevillea 447 (1993)) for details.

There are six subspecies.
 
Grevillea wickhamii Meisn. subsp. wickhamii occurs in the West Kimberley region of Western Australia, from the Mt Bell area to E of Gibb River Station, and N to Bachsten Creek and the King Edward River, also on islands of the Buccaneer Archipelago (e.g. Powerful Island, MEL727855).

Grevillea wickhamii subsp. macrodonta occurs in north-western Western Australia, from about Goldsworthy N along the coastal plain to Broome and E to Edgar Range and Derby and beyond (possibly to the Napier Range).

Grevillea wickhamii subsp. hispidula occurs in Western Australia in the Hamersley Range and Pilbara areas, and E to Lake Disappointment and Windy Corner.

Grevillea wickhamii subsp. pallida occurs in north-western Western Australia, known as yet only from a small population at the Type locality in Prince Regent Nature Reserve. Possibly also on Koolan Island.

Grevillea wickhamii subsp. aprica is widespread in northern inland Australia; in Western Australia, S of the Kimberley from Margaret River to the Northern Territory border, and disjunctly near Docker River and S of Port Hedland; throughout Northern Territory S from about Larrimah, and into NW Queensland in patchy occurrences from Lawn Hill area to Mt Isa, Cloncurry and Winton.

Grevillea wickhamii subsp. cratista occurs in northern Western Australia, known as yet only from the Bungle Bungle Range.
Three subspecies are recognised; paludosa, acanthifolia and stenomera.
This species is under taxonomic revision as it may be a species complex.
Grevillea arenaria has two recognised subspecies; arenaria and canescens.
There are two recgonised subspecies of Grevillea baueri; baueri and asperula.
There are two regonised subspecies of Grevillea buxifolia; ecorniculata and buxifolia.
The taxon is maintained as Grevillea ilicifolia var. dilatata by some references in Australia (Makinson 2000, eFloraSA 2020).
Grevillea irrasa has two recognised subspecies; irrasa and didymochiton.
There are two recognised subspecies of Grevillea obtusiflora; fecunda and obtusiflora.
Grevillea parviflora has two recognised subspecies; supplicans and parviflora.
Grevillea rhyolitica has two recognised subspecies; semivestita and rhyolitica.
This is a complex of species, some of which have very limited distribution ranges.
Grevillea scortechinii has two regconised subspecies; sarmentosa and scortechinii.
Grevillea sericea has two recognised subspecies; seriparia and sericea.

An attempt has been made to clarify what is known as the 'H. dactyloides species complex', in which several morphological variants have been informally recognised for some time, in particular resprouting and non-sprouting forms. This feature, supported by others such as branchlet indumentum and flowering time, provides the basis for recognition of a distinct taxon at species level (H. laevipes), but for many specimens for which these features are not evident or are unrecorded, assignment to the taxa recognised remains difficult. Further collecting of flowering material and field observation is expected to improve resolution of the complex.

Persoonia prostrata is very similar to specimens of P. stradbrokensis collected from the mainland south of Fraser Island, but differs in its prostrate habit, usually smaller leaves and smaller flowers. These differences are based on only two collections for P. prostrata, neither of which is an adequate specimen. It may be that P. prostrata and P. stradbrokensis are conspecific, and that P. prostrata is just a prostrate, maritime form. However, the distributions of these species are separated by over 100 km.
O. meridionalis Ng is a primary wild relative of cultivated rice (O. sativa L.) and African rice (O. glaberrima Steud.) (USDA, ARS, National Genetic Resources Program 2017).
Cenchrus basedowii is a tertiary wild relative of pearl millet C. americanus (L.) Morrone (syn. Pennisetum glaucum (L.) Br.) (USDA, ARS, GRIN 2017).

Phenetic and morphological analysis of the Banksia spinulosa Sm. complex (Proteaceae) provided strong support for the recognition of Banksia cunninghamii subsp. A at species rank under the name B. neoanglica (Stipmson et al. 2012).

The taxonomy of the genus Caldesia is far from clear and this may obscure the conservation requirements of some taxa. Most African authors have recognized Caldesia reniformis as a independent species but on a world-wide scale it seems to merge with Caldesia parnassiifolia var major (Micheli) Buchenau.
In the Flora of tropical East Africa treated as a synonym of L. perpusilla, but now generally accepted as a species in its own right.
There are three subordinate taxa of Azolla pinnata depending on the range of occurrence. Azolla pinnata africana is found Africa, A pinnata asiatica in Asia and A pinnata pinnata in Oceania.

Ceratophyllum is a complicated genus with a range of taxa named but inconsistently recognized. Cook (1970) states that the genus includes four polymorphic species, but in parts of Europe some of the morphological variants are recognised as species or at a subordinate level. Whilst at least in the west, C. demersum s.s. is so widespread and abundant that it is unlikely that taxonomic issues will affect its conservation or Red List assessment, inconsistent recording within the C. demersum complex is likely to affect the Red List assessments of any subordinate taxa assessed.

The e-Monocot website states this is a nomen illegitimum and a synonym of Cyperus exaltatus var. exaltatus. As the African Plant Database (APD 2020) upholds the species (as do the African Floras) this assessment follows the African references.
This species previously appeared on the IUCN Red List in the genus Pycreus but is now considered valid in the genus Cyperus.
A forma apetala (Wingfield) K.Lye is recognized which occurs in coastal Tanzania.
Numerous subspecies have been described within this species (Triest 1988) but these are not consistently recognised.

Marsilea minuta is quite close to M. quadrifolia, and in fact specimens of Marsilea from China seem intermediate between the two species in sporocarp size and peduncle attachment. Study of a wide range of Old World material of Marsilea would be required, however, to resolve the question of whether M. quadrifolia and M. minuta represent distinct species (Johnson 1986).

UAE Taxonomic Notes
The species is placed in genus Diplachne by Plants of the World online as Diplachne fusca (L.) P. Beauv. ex Roem. & Schult.
Plants from the sand plain region north of Perth previously included under H. corymbosa have been recognized as the distinct species, H. eneabba.

Two subspecies have been recognised but the status of subsp. needlei, virtually differing only in its narrow needle-shaped leaves and confined to a small area with populations spread over c. 10 km just south of Lake King, requires further evaluation. Hakea cygna Lamont subsp. cygna occurs across the full range of the species, and in the full range of habitats.
Populations reported from Queensland are now a different species – H. lorea lorea (Harden 1991, Barker et al. 1999).

Hakea kippistiana is closely allied to H. leucoptera. It is possible that, particularly northern records of H. kippistiana, have been confused with the H. leucoptera which is a closely allied widespread eastern and central Australian arid and semiarid species.

There are two taxa within this species, one confined to sand plains between the Stirling Range and Israelite Bay and the other from more northerly localities and overlapping in distribution with H. psilorrhyncha (and possibly H. obliqua subsp. obliqua at its most easterly distribution, although this remains to be confirmed).

Hakea obliqua subsp. obliqua occurs on the south coastal plain between Stirling Range and Israelite Bay, Western Australia, inland as far as Pingrup; whereas subsp. parviflora occurs in south-western Western Australia from about Coorow to Fitzgerald River National Park.
The three subpopulations significant genetic differences (Samson et al. 2015).

Maintained at species level because of its smaller flower size, although there appears to be no other character to separate it from the red-flowered form of H. prostrata with which it overlaps in distribution. Preiss 538 and Preiss 542 from the Darling Range, treated as H. prostrata, may also belong here. Field studies are required to clarify whether there are two distinct taxa (Flora of Australia Online; ABRS 2017).
The identity of records from Mount Ragged required conformation and are excluded form this assessment.

Two subspecies are recognised: Isopogon formosus subsp. formosus and I. formosus subsp. dasylepis, the latter is mainly confined to the region around Bunbury and Busselton, extending south to Scott River.
There are two subspecies: Isopogon panduratus subsp. palustris and I. panduratus subsp. panduratus.
There are two subspecies: Isopogon pruinosus subsp. pruinosus and I. pruinosus subsp. glabellus.

Three subspecies recognised:

Isopogon scabriusculus subsp. pubifloris, which is scattered from near Hyden to between Southern Cross and Coolgardie and south to around Lake King and Frank Hann National Park.

Isopogon scabriusculus subsp. stenophyllus, scattered from north of Wubin to around Southern Cross and Muntadgin and extending to south of Lake Grace and near Newdegate, with one isolated collection putatively from Darlington.

Isopogon scabriusculus Meisn. subsp. scabriusculus, that occurs from near Mullewa south to near Newdegate, with most collections from around Wongan Hills and Tammin.

Two geographically distinct subspecies were described in the Flora of Australia treatment and a third has since been published: Lambertia echinata subsp. echinata is known only from the type locality in south-western Western Australia; Lambertia echinata subsp. citrina occurs from Cheyne Beach on Cheyne Bay to near Albany; the third subspecies is Lambertia echinata subsp. occidentalis south of Brusselton.

Three subspecies are recognised: Synaphea petiolaris subsp. simplex, which occurs north-east of Busselton; subsp. petiolaris, widespread from Walpole east to Boyatup and inland to the Stirling Range and north to Wooroloo; and subsp. triloba which occurs in far south-western Western Australia, from Walpole to Busselton.

Three subspecies are recognised: Synaphea spinulosa subsp. major, occurs from Ballidu and Calingiri south-east to Southern Cross, south to Hopetoun and east to Israelite Bay, with outliers east to Twilight Cove; subsp. spinulosa, common north of Perth as far as the Eneabba district and south along the coastal plain to Bunbury (one inland record near York); and subsp. borealisoccurs from Kalbarri National Park south almost to Geraldton.
The sub-population of this species in Queensland is suspected to be a different species and requires a taxonomic review. In Queensland the species is known as Cyathea celebica Blume.

The identity of populations from the western end of Kangaroo Island needs confirmation, as they tend to have larger fruit and the leaves are not always short and straight as they are typically found in this species.
The species requires taxonomic review (P. Weston per. comm. 2019).
This species has four recognised varieties; brevifolia, juniperina, mollis and ulicina.
Three subspecies of Persoonia laurina are recognised; leiogyna, laurina and intermedia.

This species recognises three varieties; muelleri, angustifolia and densifolia. 















subsp. densifolia
Persoonia sericea is geographically variable, with a number of morphologically distinctive local forms, some of which may prove, on closer analysis, to be distinct species.

This species closely resembles P. fastigiata but is distinguished by its indumentum of appressed to antrorsely spreading hairs and its narrower leaves. Specimens of P. subtilis are somewhat variable in leaf length but variation within populations seems as great as that between them.
Two subspecies are recognised; terminalis and recurve.
Abelmoschus ficulneus Wall. Ex Wight & Arn. is a tertiary genetic relative of okra, A. esculenta (L.) Moench (USDA, Agricultural Research Service, National Plant Germplasm System 2019).

Abelmoschus moschatus Medik is a tertiary genetic relative of okra, A. esculentus (L.) Moench (USDA, Agricultural Research Service, National Plant Germplasm System 2020). Okra taxonomy is an area of active research and some taxonomic concepts within the Abelmoschus genus have not yet been comprehensively resolved (Patil et al. 2015, WCVP 2020). A. moschatus is one of the most polymorphic species in the genus and its intraspecific taxonomy has been subject to much debate (Patil et al. 2015). In a taxonomic revision of the genus, van Borssum Waalkes (1966) retained six Abelmoschus species, including A. moschatus, recognising three subspecies, subsp. moschatus, subsp. biakensis, and subsp. tuberosus. However, it is currently accepted that subsp. tuberosus is synonymous with A. sagittifolius (Wu et al. 2007, Patil et al. 2018, WCVP 2020) and the status of subsp, biakensis 0;requires verification (WCVP 2020). Accordingly, records identified as these subspecies have been excluded from analysis. Much more data are necessary to fully understand the relationships among species in the Abelmoschus ;genus, their intraspecific delimitation, and the possible roles of past hybridisation events (Werner et al. 2015).

Three varieties of this orchid have been recognized Dendrobium canaliculatum var. foelschei, D. canaliculatum var. nigrescens and D. canaliculatum var. pallidum but Cribb (1986) considers that the var. nigresecens is doubtful, as intermediates are common, and the var. pallidum is an albino variant.

Several varieties of this variable species are recognised for example, the yellow form var. broomfieldii Fitzg. Two other varieties are recognised in Australia: var. fimbrilabium Reichb. f. which has fimbriate side lobes to the lip and is also found in New Guinea; and var. fuscum. Var. albertisiana  and var. gracile are recognised from New Guinea (Cribb 1986).

This species has sometimes been confused with Dendrobium trilamellatum which is found in much dryer open forests (P. Adams pers. comm. 2019). Generally, D. johannis flowers in autumn in Australia and has dark petals and sepals with a yellow lip and has a musky perfume; while D. trilamellatum flowers in spring and has more or less uniformly yellow-brown segments and a sweet perfume. The two were not thought to be sufficiently different to be regarded as separate species and were maintained as varieties in the second edition of Australian Indigenous Orchids (Dockrill 1992) (P. Lavarack pers. comm. 2019).
Other heterotypic synonyms are listed in the World Checklist of Selected Plant Families (2018).
Other heterotypic synonyms are listed in the World Checklist of Selected Plant Families (2018).

Other heterotypic synonyms are listed by the World Checklist of Selected Plant Families (WCSP 2018). This taxon is called Rhinerrhizopsis moorei in the Australian Plant Census. However, Jones and Clements (2006) consider Australian populations of the genus Rhinerrhizopsis to be a separate species, R. matutina, distinct from non-Australian R. moorei (DEHWA 2008) and they also recognise three species within New Guinea. They are not followed by more recent authors in this.
Eucalyptus leucoxylon includes four subspecies; leucoxylon, stephaniae, pruinosa and megalocarpa.

This species is considered in between Eucalyptus arachnaea and E. pluricaulis by French (2012) and Nicolle (2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.
This species may be a hybrid between Eucalyptus petraea or E. cuprea and E. loxophleba, although there is not strong evidence of this currently (French 2012).

This species is considered a hybrid between Eucalyptus loxophleba and E. accedens (M. French pers. comm. 2018, Nicolle 2018). It is considered Data Deficient in this assessment until the taxonomy is resolved.
Includes Eucalyptus erythronema subsp. erythronema and E. erythronema subsp. inornata.
This species is considered dubious, possibly Eucalyptus eugenioides by Nicolle (2018). It is considered as distinct by A. Bean (pers. comm. 2019) and thus is assessed at species level here.
This species is considered a hybrid between Corymbia dendromerinx and C. flavescens by Nicolle (2013). Without further evidence it is considered at species rank in this assessment.
This species is closely related to four other species of fully rough-barked bloodwoods; Corymbia novoguinensis, C. polycarpa, C. plena and C. ligans.

At the southern end of the range this species intergrades with Eucalyptus microcarpa and in the north-eastern portion of its range with E. moluccana. Typically the adult leaves of this species are narrower (less than 1.5 cm side) than both E. microcarpa and E. moluccana.
This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus brachycalyx by Nicolle (2018) and M. French (pers. comm. 2018). It is assessed as Data Deficient here until its taxonomy can be resolved.
This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus paniculata by Nicolle (2018) and K. Rule (pers. comm. 2018).
Eucalyptus parramattensis includes three subspecies; decadens, parramattensis and sphaerocalyx.

Eucalyptus quinniorum is considered synonymous with E. cypellocarpa by Nicolle (2018) and G. Phillips (pers. comm. 2019). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) hence both species are assessed separately until the taxonomy is resolved.

This species is regarded as synonymous with Eucalyptus tenera (M. French pers. comm. 2019) although is still accepted at species rank in the Australia Plant Name Index. This species is assessed here as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

This species is considered dubious by Nicolle (2018). According to A.
