Bean (pers. comm. 2019) this species is likely a subspecies of Eucalyptus mannifera. The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

This species is considered a hybrid between Eucalyptus buprestium and E. pachyloma by Nicolle (2018), but is accepted by M. French (pers. comm. 2019) and S. Hopper (pers. comm. 2018). It is therefore accepted as a good species rank for this assessment.

This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus cypellocarpa by Nicolle (2018) and G. Phillips (pers. comm. 2019). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) but is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.
This species is closely related to Eucalyptus tenuiramis.

Eucalyptus surgens is considered synonymous with E. scyphocalyx (M. French pers. comm. 2018, Nicolle 2018). Surveys and associated research are currently being undertaken in the type locality of E. surgens to confirm its species rank (S. Hopper pers. comm. 2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) hence both are assessed sepaarately until the taxonomy is resolved.

The species is closely related to Eucalyptus odorata (Rule 1994) and is considered a synonym of this species by Nicolle (2018). The taxon is maintained at species rank by Rule (2018) and is assessed accordingly here.

Eucalyptus paralimnetica is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus spreta (M. French pers. comm. 2018, Nicolle 2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) hence both are assessed separately until the taxonomy is resolved.

This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus scyphocalyx (M. French pers. comm. 2018, Nicolle 2018). Surveys and associated research are currently being undertaken in the type locality of this taxon to confirm its species rank (S. Hopper pers. comm. 2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) but is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

This species is considered dubious by Nicolle (2018); possibly synonymous with Eucalyptus tenera (M. French, pers. comm. 2019). However, the species is generally distinct within its range and should remain at species rank until a full taxonomic revision of its group is undertaken (M. French pers. comm. 2019).
Includes Eucalyptus wandoo subsp. wandoo and E. wandoo subsp. pulvera.

Eucalyptus cuspidata is considered synonymous with E. angulosa (M. French pers. comm. 2018, Nicolle 2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) hence both taxa are assessed separately until the taxonomy is resolved.
Nicolle (2018) considers this taxa a hybrid between Eucalyptus camphora and E. strzleckii. However, Rule (2012) maintains the taxa is distinct and it is assessed accordingly here.
This species is closely related to Eucalyptus newbeyi and E. megacornuta.

The species may be a hybrid between Eucalyptus platypus and E. occidentalis (M. French pers. comm. 2018, Nicolle 2018), but requires further study (S. Hopper pers. comm. 2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

According to Department of the Environment (2014), Johnson and Hill (1990) consider this taxa a hybrid between Eucalyptus stellulata and E. moorei, although it appears this refers to a discussion pertaining to E. latiuscula (later recognised as E. moorei). Hill and Johnson (1991) describe this species as intermediate in many characteristics between E. stellulata and E. moorei, although argue for its species rank. The species is not recognised by Nicolle (2018) and the trees grown at Mt Annan Botanic Gardens resemble E. moorei (G. Phillips pers. comm. 2018), who also considers the species a potential hybrid. The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus litorea (M. French pers. comm. 2018, Nicolle 2018). This name is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.
This species is closely related to, but generally distinct from Eucalyptus tereticornis (S. Bell pers. comm. 2018, G. Phillips pers. comm. 2019).
This species is considered a possible synonym of Eucalyptus rudderi by Nicolle (2018). G. Phillips (pers. comm. 2019) also considered the taxonomy of this species uncertain.
This species is closely related to Eucalyptus baxteri (Brooker and Kleinig 2006).
This species is closely related to Eucalyptus tereticornis, but distinct within its range (J. Halford pers. comm. 2019).

This species is potentially a hybrid between Eucalyptus accedens and E. zopherophloia (M. French pers. comm. 2018, Nicolle 2018), but the taxa requires further study (S. Hopper pers. comm.2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

Eucalyptus famelica species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus litorea (M. French pers. comm. 2018, Nicolle 2018). This name is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) hence both species are assessed separately here until the taxonomy is resolved.
The subpopulations previously attributed as this species that occur further north in the vicinity of Dalveen will be described as a new taxon.

This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus subtilis (M. French pers. comm. 2018, Nicolle 2018). It is still accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and therefore considered Data Deficient in this assessment until the taxonomy is resolved.
Includes Eucalyptus mimica subsp. mimica and Eucalyptus mimica subsp. continens.

This species is considered dubious, possibly Eucalyptus falciformis by Nicolle (2018). Although the species is considered sufficiently distinct to be assessed at species level (N. Walsh pers. comm. 2018, G. Phillips pers. comm. 2019, K. Rule pers. comm. 2018).
Although detailed taxonomic investigation is yet to be completed, there is little evidence of introgression between Eucalyptus nebulosa and the sympatric and closely-related E. nitida (Gray 2008).

Eucalyptus oleosa includes subsp. ampliata, corvina, cylindroidea, oleosa, that are distributed across southern Australia and characterised by seedling leaves that form a spiral around the stem (French 2012).
Eucalyptus diversifolia includes two subspecies: diversifolia and hesperia.
Eucalyptus polyanthemos includes four subspecies; vestita, longor, polyanthemos, and marginalis.

Angophora inopina is considered taxonomically similar to A. floribunda and A. crassifolia (S. Bell pers. comm., 2018). This species is considered dubious by Nicolle (2018) as it is possibly A. crassifolia. According to G. Phillips (pers. comm. 2019), the species is generally distinct within its range, and it has therefore been accepted at species rank in this assessment.

This species may be a stable hybrid of Eucalyptus ovata and E. cosmophylla, although this is not universally accepted and the species is distinct within its range (Nicolle 2013). The taxa is therefore accepted at species rank for this assessment.
This species is considered dubious by Nicolle (2018). According to K. Rule (pers. comm. 2018) the species is distinct and should be accepted at species rank for this assessment.

This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus elata by Nicolle (2018). According to K. Rule (pers. comm. 2018) the species is closely related to E. elata but sufficiently distinct to be assessed at species level.
A subspecies of Eucalyptus. mooreana has been recently described as E. revelata (Nicolle and Barrett 2018); this is assessed separately here.

This species is considered a hybrid between Eucalyptus subterea and E. todtiana (M. French pers. comm. 2018, Nicolle 2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.
Eucalyptus sargentii includes two subspecies; E. sargentii subsp. onesia and E. sargentii subsp. sargentii.
Includes Eucalyptus spathulata subsp. spathulata and E. spathulata subsp. salina.
Includes Eucalyptus subangusta subsp. subangusta, E. subangusta, subsp. cerina, E. subangusta subsp. pusilla and E. subangusta subsp. virescens.

Eucalyptus microschema is considered synonymous with E. subtilis (M. French pers. comm. 2018, Nicolle 2018). It is still accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and therefore both species are assessed separately until the taxonomy is resolved.

Eucalyptus depauperata is regarded as synonymous with E. tenera (M. French pers. comm. 2019) although is still accepted at species rank in the Australia Plant Name Index. Both species are assessed here separately until the taxonomy is resolved.
Includes Eucalyptus vegrandis subsp. vegrandis and E. vegrandis subsp. recondita.
This species is closely related to, but distinct from Eucalyptus platypus (French 2012).
This species is considered dubious by Nicolle (2018), possibly Eucalyptus insulana; but distinct by A. Bean (pers. comm. 2019). It is therefore considered at species rank in this assessment.

According to Brooker and Hopper (1993), the species appears to have no affinity with other related species, although there is a small possibility that it is a rare hybrid between Eucalyptus marginata and another species (Brooker and Hopper 1993). This species is considered a hybrid by Malcom French (pers. comm. 2018) and Nicolle (2018). Further study is required according to S. Hopper (pers. comm. 2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

This species may be a hybrid of Eucalyptus drummondii, but on morphological grounds, no other parent is discernible (Grayling and Brooker 1998, Nicolle 2018, M. French pers. comm. 2018). Despite profuse flowering and fruiting, no viable seeds have been collected, and pollen fertility is low (20-40%) (Grayling and Brooker 1998). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.
This species includes Eucalyptus approximans subsp. approximans and E. approximans subsp. codonocarpa.
This species is closely related to Eucalyptus lehmannii.

Eucalyptus arcana is also recorded at Moonlight Head in Victoria but there is considerable doubt about the identity of this subpopulation. Chappill, Ladiges and Boland (1986) identified the trees at Moonlight Head as E. aromaphloia. Seedlings raised from the subpopulation also indicate E. aromaphloia. Bark, juvenile leaves, buds and fruits also indicate E. aromaphloia. The bark at Moonlight Head is more stringy than tessellated as for true E. arcana (Rule 2009).
This species is closely related to Eucalyptus taurina.
Eucalyptus pleurocorys is considered synonymous with E. brachycalyx by Nicolle (2018) and M. French (pers. comm. 2018). Both species are assessed separately here until the taxonomy can be resolved.
Includes Eucalyptus caesia subsp. caesia and E. caesia subsp. magna.

Includes Eucalyptus calycogona subsp. miracula, E. calycogona subsp. calycogona,
E. calycogona subsp. gracilis, E. calycogona subsp. spaffordii and E. calycogona subsp. trachybasis.

The species is very closely related to Eucalyptus rubida and has previously been regarded as a subspecies (Brooker and Kleinig 2006). It is not accepted by Nicolle (2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

This species is considered a hybrid between Eucalyptus cypellocarpa and E. goniocalyx by Nicolle (2018), but is considered a distinct species by K. Rule (pers. comm. 2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed at species rank here.
Eucalyptus celastroides includes two subspecies; virella and celastroides.

This species is considered a hybrid between Eucalyptus aenea and E. microcarpa by Nicolle (2018) and should be assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved (G. Phillips pers. comm. 2018).

The taxa is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus corticosa and E. ignorabilis by Nicolle (2018). However, Rule (2012) maintains the taxa are sufficiently distinct, and thus they are assessed at species level here.

This species is considered a stable hybrid between Eucalyptus pleuracarpa and E. gittinsii (M. French pers. comm. 2018, S. Hopper pers. comm. 2018). It is still accepted at species rank in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is therefore considered Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.
This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus tectifica by Nicolle (2018). Without stronger evidence against Hill and Johnson (2000), this taxa is assessed at species rank here.

This species is considered a hybrid between Eucalyptus largiflorens and E. odorata by (Nicolle 2018) but distinct by K. Rule, pers. comm. (2018) and Rule (2018). It is accepted at species level in this assessment.

This species is considered dubious by Nicolle (2018), possibly Corymbia brachycarpa; however, it is considered a distinct species by R. Fensham (pers. comm. 2018) and A. Bean, pers. comm. (2019). It has therefore been accepted at species rank in this assessment.

This species is considered dubious by Nicolle (2018), possibly Corymbia aparrenrinja; although is generally distinct within its range (R. Fensham pers. comm. 2019). It has therefore been accepted at species rank in this assessment.
This species includes two subspecies; Corymbia watsoniana subsp. capillata and C. watsoniana subsp. watsoniana (Brooker and Kleinig 2004).

This species is considered synonymous with Angophora subvelutina by Nicolle (2018). This species is considered by G. Phillips (pers. comm. 2019) to be generally distinct within its range and has therefore been accepted at species rank for this assessment.
This species is closely-related to Eucalyptus orbifolia.

This species is considered taxonomically uncertain (M. French pers. comm. 2019) and a hybrid between Eucalyptus spreta and E. vittata by Nicolle (2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) but is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.
This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus volcanica by Nicolle (2018) and G. Phillips (pers. comm. 2019). It is assessed as Data Deficient until its taxonomy is resolved.

The species is considered by some experts to be a hybrid between Eucalyptus arachnaea and E. accedens (M. French pers. comm. 2018, Nicolle 2018), although this needs to be confirmed with molecular evidence (S. Hopper pers. comm. 2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) but is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.
This species includes subsp. crucis, subsp. lanceolata and subsp. praecipua (French 2012).

This species is considered dubious by Nicolle (2018), possibly Eucalyptus caleyi; although is considered sufficiently distinct to remain at species level for this assessment (A. Bean pers. comm. 2018).
Includes Eucalyptus flocktoniae subsp. flocktoniae and E. flocktoniae subsp. hebes.

This species is probably synonymous with Eucalyptus stellulata (Nicolle 2018), and is not a reliable taxa (G. Phillips pers. comm. 2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

This species is considered dubious, possibly Eucalyptus ophitica by Nicolle (2018). According to G. Phillips (pers. comm. 2019) the taxon is generally distinct within its range and is therefore accepted at species level for this assessment.
This species is closely related to Eucalyptus nudicaulis and E. flindersii (Nicolle 2013).
This species is considered taxonomically dubious by Nicolle (2018) who suggests it may be Eucalyptus punctata; and a minor variation of E. longirostrata by A. Bean (pers. comm. 2019).
This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus medialis (M. French pers. comm. 2018). It is treated as a good species here.

Eucalyptus luteola is considered synonymous with E. histophylla (Nicolle 2018). Field research in 2019 will confirm this (M. French pers. comm. 2019). Until this is confirmed they are assessed sepaartely.

The taxa is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus corticosa and E. conferta by Nicolle (2018). Although Rule (2012) maintains the taxa are sufficiently distinct, and thus they are assessed at species level here.
This species is considered a hybrid between Eucalyptus macrocarpa and E. pyriformis by Nicolle (2018). According to French (2012) the taxon should be accepted at species rank.

This species is considered a possible integrade of Eucalyptus ravida and E. tortilis by Nicolle (2018). According to M. French (pers. comm. 2019) the taxon is distinct and should remain at species level for assessment.
Includes Eucalyptus kochii subsp. kochii, E. kochii subsp. borealis, E. kochii subsp. plenissima and E. kochii subsp. yellowdinensis.
This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus leucophylla by Nicolle (2018) and M. French (pers. comm. 2019).
Eucalyptus loxopleba includes four subspecies; loxophleba, supralaevis, lissophloia and gratiae.
This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus histophylla (Nicolle 2018). Field research in 2019 will confirm this (M. French pers. comm. 2019).
Eucalyptus macrocarpa includes two subspecies; E. macrocarpa subsp. macrocarpa and E. macrocarpa subsp. elachantha.
The species is very closely related to Eucalyptus caliginosa.

This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus hebetifolia by Nicolle (2018) and M. French (pers. comm. 2019). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) but is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

The species is closely allied to some species with which it co-occurs. At the northern end of its range the morphology of the tree grades into the closely related Eucalyptus woollsiana. In South Australia the species can be confused with E. odorata and E. cajuputea (see Nicolle 2013) and E. silvestris and E. wimmerensis (Rule 2018). There are characters associated with bark texture and juvenille leaves separating some of these species but the single-stemmed habit E. microcarpa compared to the multi-stemmed mallee-form habit of the other species is most useful in the field.

This species is closely related to Eucalyptus cajuputea, E. wimmerensis and E. albopurpuea. E. cajuputea tends to occupy more arid regions; E. wimmerensis is restricted to the Bordertown district of South Australia and has narrower leaves and smaller buds; and E. albopurpureahas broader juvenile leaves and larger buds and fruit (Nicolle 2013).

This species is considered dubious by Nicolle (2018), possibly Eucalyptus atrata; and taxonomically uncertain by K. Rule (pers. comm. 2019). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus spreta (M. French pers. comm. 2018,Nicolle 2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) but is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus paniculata (Nicolle 2018). This species is also considered to be taxonomically uncertain by G. Phillips (pers. comm. 2019) and A. Bean (pers. comm. 2019). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) but is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.
This assessment recognized four varieties of Acacia tumida (var. tumida, var. kulparn, var. pilbarensis, var. extenta). All varieties are considered for this assessment.

Allium triquetrum L. is a tertiary wild relative of a number of crops in the Allium group, including onion (A. cepa L.), Welsh onion (A. fistulosum L.), leek (A. porrum L.), garlic (A. sativum L.) and chives (A. schoenoprasum L.).
Closely related to Eucalyptus kingsmillii.

This species is taxonomically uncertain. The species has previously been considered a subspecies of Eucalyptus camphora (Brooker and Kleinig 2006) and is not recognised by Nicolle (2018). The name is currently recognised by the NSW Herbarium described by Wiecke (2011). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved on the advice of G. Phillips (pers. comm. 2019).

The taxa is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus ignorabilis and E. conferta by Nicolle (2018). Although Rule (2012) maintains the taxa are sufficiently distinct, and thus they are assessed at species level here.

This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus angulosa (M. French pers. comm. 2018, Nicolle 2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) but is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

This species is considered synonymous with Eucalyptus polybractea by Nicolle (2018). The taxa is part of the 'grey-box complex' and is generally distinct within its range (Rule 2018). It is therefore assessed at species rank here.

The species is considered to be an hybrid between Eucalyptus wimmerensis and E. microcarpa by Nicolle (2018). According to Rule (2018) this species is distinct and is therefore assessed at species level here.

This species is taxonomically uncertain and closely related to Eucalyptus macrorhyncha or E. mackintii (K. Rule pers. comm. 2018). According to Nicolle (2018) the species is a probable hybrid involving E. kybeanensis. The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

The species should be considered as a subspecies of Eucalyptus alatocaulis (K. Rule pers. comm. December 2018, Nicolle 2018). The species is currently accepted in the Australian Plant Name Index (February 2019) and is assessed as Data Deficient until the taxonomy is resolved.

This species is considered a hybrid between Eucalyptus wimmerensis and E. microcarpa by Nicolle (2018) but is regarded as a distinct species by K. Rule (pers. comm. 2018) and Rule (2018). It is accepted at species rank in this assessment.

This species is regarded as dubious by Nicolle (2018); possibly synonymous with Eucalyptus cajuputea. However, Rule (2018) maintains that there are consistent characters relating to tree-form, bark, juvenile leaves and adult leaves separating these two species. Furthermore, the two species as circumscribed by Rule (2018) do not co-occur and they have distinctly different rates of decline.
This can be divided in two subspecies: pygmaeus is mainly a tropical or subtropical species, while michelianus is more widespread.

This species can be regarded as the tropical counterpart of Phragmites australis; as noted by Cope (1982) (Cope, T.A. 1982 Flora of Pakistan No. 143. Poaceae. Jointly published by the Institute of Plant Conservation, University of Karachi and Missouri Botanical Press) "for most of their range these two species of Phragmites are allopatric. Phragmites australis is a temperate species while Phragmites karka is tropical". However, different approaches to recognition of taxa within the genus and uncertainty about taxonomy in some areas make it difficult to establish the precise distribution and status of this taxon.
The taxonomy requires clarification and may in fact represent more than one species. This assessment includes the various taxonomic entities pending taxonomic clarification.
The record from Western Australia has been excluded from this assessment as it is believed to refer to a different taxon.

Morphological and ecological differences between the sub-populations in the Kimberley and in Northern Territory suggest that these actually represent different taxa, however as these have not been described, for the purposes of this assessment they are treated as one taxon.

From 1976 until 1983, nomenclatural confusion designated Paspalum distichum for P. vaginatum and Paspalum paspaloides for P. distichum (Schulz 1962, Guedes 1976, 1981; Fosberg 1977, Renvoize and Clayton 1980). The matter was resolved in 1983 (Brummitt 1983) and appropriate taxonomic and morphological distinctions can be found in Echarte and Clausen (1993) and Webster (1987).

The main difference between the two species is that P. vaginatum inherently colonizes saline ecosystems while P. distichum can be found in freshwater habitats. Genetically, they are quite distinct (Echarte and Clausen 1993), and the two species can be differentiated by 20 morphological traits [adapted from Duncan 1997].

Australian representatives of this species were initially described as Mallotus didymochryseus Airy Shaw (1981) in recognition of its similarity to this species in Papua New Guinea (PNG). However, M. dispersus has notable differences to M. didymochryseus in foliage, floral and size characteristics, and occupies different habitats. Consequently, the revised taxonomy now recognises M. dispersus as distinct from M. didymochryseus, and note that M. dispersus occurs in northern Australia and southern PNG (Forster, 1999).

According to Häkkinen (2013), Musa fitzalanii F.Muell. is assigned to Musa sect. Callimusa Cheesman. By this definition, M. fitzalanii is a wild relative of Manila hemp, M. textilis Née., and Fe'i bananas, under Taxon Group 2, and a wild relative of edible crop bananas and plantains under Taxon group 4, according to the taxon group definition by Maxted et al. (2006). However, it should be noted that Häkkinen's classification does not have universal contemporary support (J. Daniells pers. comm. 2020), and recent accounts contend the validity of the ascribed sections (Daniells and Janssens 2020). Additionally, for M. fitzalanii in particular, the decision to reassign the taxon to section Callimusa from the former section Eumusa does not appear to be evidence-based (J. Daniells pers. comm. 2020). At present, though, an alternative contemporary classification scheme has not been formally proposed, so for now this classification is retained to define relatedness to the crop.

Musa fitzalanii has been widely accepted as a distinct species (Ross 1987, Hnatiuk 1990, Häkkinen 2013, Department of the Environment 2020, WCSP 2020). At present, there is insufficient evidence to disprove its specific status; however, it is likewise challenging to prove its taxonomic distinctness (J. Daniells pers. comm. 2020). Simmonds (1956) considered the species likely to be allied to M. schizocarpa and this remains a possibility (J. Daniells pers. comm. 2020). Further research into the taxonomy of the species is necessary, yet availability of suitable genetic material with which to conduct such research may be a limiting factor.

According to Häkkinen (2013), Musa jackeyi W.Hill is assigned to Musa sect. Callimusa Cheesman. By this definition, M. jackeyi is a wild relative of Manila hemp, M. textilis Née., and Fe'i bananas, under Taxon Group 2, and a wild relative of edible crop bananas and plantains under Taxon group 4, according to the taxon group definition by Maxted et al. (2006). However, it should be noted that Häkkinen's classification does not have universal contemporary support (J. Daniells pers. comm. 2020), and recent accounts contend the validity of the ascribed sections (Daniells and Janssens 2020). At present, though, an alternative contemporary classification scheme has not been formally proposed, so for now this classification is retained to define relatedness to the crop.

This is an accepted species (Board of Trustees, RBG Kew 2020) but Adema (2003) lists this under 'dubious species'. The type specimen is fragmentary (one leaflet and part of a pod) and the material is similar to Derris koolgibberah Verdc. and D. submontana Verdc.
Three varieties of this species are recognized: var maculata, var. appressepilosa and var. elongata (Bosman and de Haas 1983).
Cordia myxa is morphologically close to Cordia dichotoma G.Forst., and the species are often confused (Oudhia 2007).
Owing to confusion with Flueggea virosa, compounded by overlapping ranges, many reports of F. leucopyrus require confirmation (Webster 1984).
Calophyllum lonchophyllum is a name of uncertain application. Originally described in 1927, no further reference to this species has been found.

Acacia armitii is a small tree found in the northern regions of the Northern Territory (NT) and Queensland (Qld) in Australia.  Throughout its range there are a number of similar species that are each distinguished by different characteristics, these species are: A. plectocarpa subsp. plectocarpa; A. plectocarpa subsp. tanumbirinensis; A. echinuliflora and A. torulosa (Wearne 2012). The former two species can be distinguished from A. armitii  by their vegetative characteristics, however the last two species need to be flowering or fruiting to clearly distinguish them in the field. The last species, A. torulosa, is widespread across much of northern Australia but can be distinguished from A. armitii because A. armitii has small (2.7-5.5 cm long), sticky, resinous pods with transverse seeds; in contrast A. torulosa's pods are longer (up to 10cm), glabrous (hairless), moniliform and has longitudinally wrinkled ridges (Pedley 1987, Wearne 2012; Kodela 2020). Acacia echinuliflora, a NT endemic, is distinguished from A. armitii by floral characteristics, this species has narrower flower-spikes and wider pods and petals with dense, patent, yellow hairs (Wearne 2012, Maslin 2018).
Two infraspecific varieties are recognised, var. desertorum and var. nudipes R.S.Cowan & Maslin (POWO 2019).

Acacia sulcata R.Br. is a highly variable species. Three varieties have been recognised, var. sulcata, var. platyphylla Maiden & Blakely and var. planoconvexa R.S.Cowan & Maslin, but future studies may demonstrate the need for further revision (Cowan and Maslin 1993, Cowan 2001).

Indigofera schultziana F.Muell. is closely related to I. saxicola Benth., and there are a number of specimens that appear to represent intergrades between the two species (Wilson and Rowe 2004, P. Wilson pers. comm. 2020). When these were first identified, the regional conservation listing of Indigofera schultziana was altered from Vulnerable to Data Deficient (Holmes et al. 2005). However, the species status for I. schultziana is upheld, and the intergrade forms are not likely to impact its extinction risk status (P. Wilson pers. comm. 2020).

Crisp and Taylor (1987) published a new combination in Leptosema for Brachysema daviesioides. In older collections and some literature about this species, Brachysema daviesioides remains the nomenclature applied.

De Wit (1956) proposed seven genera in the tribe Bauhinieae, including Lysiphyllum which had originally been described as a section of Bauhinia. This was rejected by Hutchinson (1964) who referred all genera recognized by de Wit to Bauhinia (Pedley 1977). Whilst many have accepted de Wit's nomenclature (Board of Trustees, RBG Kew 2020), much of the literature still refers to Lysiphyllum binatum as Bauhinia binata.

Most Australian "cassias" occur in large and variable populations that integrate into hybrid swarms maintained by asexual and sexual reproduction. This makes it difficult to separate them into species. There are two ways of dealing with this: one way reduces the number of variants formerly regarded as separate species into subspecies of two widespread species, one of which is Senna glutinosa. The other way, is to treat the hybrid forms into "form taxa", where separation is based on appearance but taxonomic rank is not defined. For the purposes of assessing this species we have chosen the first approach. In which case S. glutinosa includes the following: S. glutinosa ssp.chatelainiana (Green Acacia), spp. glutinosa (Sticky Acacia), nothossp. luerssenii (White Acacia) and ssp. pruinosa (White Acacia) (Moore 2005).
Records of B. insulana from China are erroneous, misidentifications of B. balansae (Wu et al. 2008).
None, described in 1957.
No doubts about its distinctness.
Resolved from the A. verniciflua/A. leprosa complex by Maslin and Murphy (2009), but there is no contention about its distinctness.
Segregated from the Tasmanian endemic A. monilifera by L.A.S. Johnson (1989), but there is no contention about its distinctness.

Acacia hopperiana is a taxonomically well-accepted species, except that plants in the northern and southern disjunct populations have slightly different seed morphology; further study may indicate that these may be best regarded as separate taxa.

There are no recognised varieties or subspecies.

Acacia multispicata is a taxonomically difficult species. It is very variable throughout its range, and further close examination and field work could see it divided into several species.

 

There are no recognised varieties or subspecies.
This taxon was formerly recognised as a subspecies of Acacia juncifolia Benth. (Maslin 2001), but is now treated as a distinct species (Maslin (coordinator) 2018, POWO 2019).
Initially described in the genus Baeckea L., the taxon was transferred to the south-western Australian genus Astartea (Myrtaceae) as part of a recent taxonomic treatment (Rye 2006).

Stylidium amabile was previously thought to represent a disjunct population of the rare Wongan Hills trigger plant (S. coroniforme); however, the species status of the taxon is well supported by morphological distinction and genetic analysis (Wege and Coates 2007).

The species is close to Dalbergia stipulacea Roxb. from continental Southeast Asia, and has incorrectly been cited as a synonym of this species in the literature. They can be distinguished by inflorescences, stipules, fruits and seeds (Sunarno and Ohashi 1996).

G.Bentham spelled the epithet "omalophylla" in London J. Bot. 1: 365 (1842) following A.Cunningham's manuscript name (see L.Pedley, Austrobaileya 1: 200 (1978)). Bentham himself later corrected the name to "homalophylla" in Fl. Austral. 2: 383 (1864), which is etymologically more correct under ICBN Rec. 60A.2 (Vienna Code, 2006). The later orthography is followed in the Australian Plant Census (APC), whereas the original epithet, "omalophylla" is followed in the International Plant Names Index (IPNI), and consequently used here.
Herbarium specimens are not always easy to discern from E. reticulatus, though they are readily distinguished in the field (Coode 1984).

Acacia leprosa had for some time been treated as a complex comprised of several variants, and is often confused with the closely related A. verniciflua complex. A taxonomic revision of the Acacia leprosa - A. verniciflua group by B.R. Maslin & D.J. Murphy (Muelleria, 2009) resulted in several new taxa. An unusual red-flowered form of a large bracteole variant of A. leprosa var. uninervia was discovered in Victoria in 1995 and is known as the cultivar Acacia leprosa 'Scarlet Blaze'.

According to Häkkinen (2013), Musa banksii F.Muell. is assigned to Musa sect. Musa Cheesman. The species is believed to be the ancestral parent of the majority of edible banana cultivars, including the East African Highland banana cultivars, contributing the 'A' genome (FAO 2010, Němečková et al. 2018). Its progenitor status would give cause to believe that Musa banksii should be classed as a primary wild relative of edible crop bananas and plantains under Gene Pool 1B (GP1B), according to the Harlan and De Wet (1971) Gene Pool Concept; however, it is more appropriate to view the species as a tertiary wild relative of edible crop bananas and plantains under Gene Pool 3 (GP3) as crossing with the crop is not possible without using highly sophisticated methods due to parthenocarpy and sterility in the crop (Sardos et al. 2016). M. banksii may also be defined as a wild relative of edible crop bananas and plantains under Taxon Group 2, according to the taxon group definition by Maxted et al. (2006).

Simmonds (1956) reduced M. banksii under M. acuminata and, following this, the synonym M. acuminata subsp. banksii has been frequently applied in literature around the species (Pollefeys et al. 2004, De Langhe 2009). Argent (1976) chose to treat is as distinct species and this was largely supported in a numerical taxonomic treatment by Simmonds and Weatherup (1990); many sources now accept M. banksii as a species in its own right (Häkkinen & Väre 2008, USDA, Agricultural Research Service, National Plant Germplasm System 2019, WCSP 2019). It should be noted that there remains uncertainty: recent genomic analyses support the classification of banksii as a subspecies of Musa acuminata (Janssens et al. 2016, Rouard et al. 2018), while Liu et al. (2019) maintain its species status following assembly of the complete chloroplast genome sequence.

The NSW Scientific Committee (2014) state that the species “was first described in 1968 (Brinsley 1968) as a variety of Caladenia carnea, but has since been elevated to species status (The Royal Botanic Gardens and Domain Trust PlantNET accessed August 2013). It is synonymous with Petalochilus attenuatus.”

Rhizanthella gardneri has been split into two species in a published paper (Dixon and Christenhusz 2018), which has been accepted by the Western Australia (WA) Herbarium. The name Rhizanthella johnstonii was added to the WA plant census in March 2018.

There are two subspecies recognized in the species (subsp. heteroclita and subsp. valida). Subspecies valida is restricted to the Porongurup Range, c. 35 km NE Albany, which is entirely enclosed in the Porongurup National Park. It is unlikely this subspecies will be elevated to specific rank, but even so this will have little bearing on the species distribution.

A highly variable species composed of 4 named varieties (var. glaberrima, var. goadbyi, var. pulchella and var. reflexa). Taxonomic changes are foreshadowed but the taxonomic level of the proposed changes has not been finalized. It is doubtful if any of the changes will affect the conservation status of the species.

There are 3 subspecies recognized in the species (subsp. viminea, subsp. appressa and subsp. demissa) which are based on leaf morphology (Crowley et al. 1990). All of these subspecies are widespread and well conserved, none are proposed to be elevated to species level..

Acacia daphnifolia is closely related to A. microbotrya, which occurs south of its range and is taller with paler flowers and usually longer, drooping phyllodes. The two species overlap in distribution and it can be difficult assigning specimens in the overlap zone. Acacia daphnifolia was treated as part of a broadly defined A. microbotrya by B.R.Maslin in the Flora of Australia (2001), but has since been accepted by the same author as a distinct species based on both morphological and genetic evidence (see Binks et al. 2015). The phyllodes of A. daphnifolia are quite variable, perhaps because of neoteny (the retention of juvenile foliage in some mature adults). There are no recognised varieties or subspecies.

Calothamnus rupestris is a taxonomically well-accepted species. The genus Calothamnus is one of many genera that are nested within the large genus Melaleuca; it was transferred to Melaleuca by Craven & R.D.Edwards in 2014. However, due to the perceived disruption that will occur when all nested genera (including Callistemon etc.) are accepted in a broadly-define Melaleuca, the Australian botanical community has on the whole not taken up this transfer and the species is currently still accepted in Calothamnus.

 

There are no recognised varieties or subspecies.

Lamarchea hakeifolia is a taxonomically well-accepted species. The genus Lamarchea is one of many genera that are nested within the large genus Melaleuca; it was transferred to Melaleuca by Craven & R.D.Edwards in 2014. However, due to the perceived disruption that will occur when all nested genera (including Calothamnus, Callistemon etc.) are accepted in a broadly-define Melaleuca, the Australian botanical community has on the whole not taken up this transfer and the species is currently still accepted in Lamarchea.

 

There are two recognised varieties: var. hakeifolia is restricted to the Peron Peninsula in Shark Bay, with var. brevifolia is more widespread and occurs inland and south of Shark Bay. There is some indication that intermediates occur between the two varieties.

Hibiscus tiliaceus is a widespread and well-known tropical and subtropical coastal species. Variety tiliaceaus is largely Old World occurring on the shores of the Indian Ocean and around much of the Pacific Basin whereas variety pernambucucensis is a New World variant occurring on both the Atlantic and Pacific shores of the American tropics. A small group of additional species, each of more limited distribution are centred taxonomically around these two taxa forming a natural group. This group is sometimes treated as a section within Hibiscus or separately from Hibiscus under a different genus (e.g. as Talipariti following Fryxell 2001). Sometimes the species are lumped into one or a few species. This group is kept under a broad concept of Hibiscus following Pfeil and Crisp (2005).
